{"term":"2015","caseName":"Kansas v. Carr","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2015/14-449","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument (No. 14-449) - October 07, 2015","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/24000","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear argument next in Case No. 14-449. On the severance question, Mr. McAllister.","start":0,"stop":4.06,"duration":4.06}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: The joint sentencing proceeding in these cases did not violate the Eighth Amendment because each defendant received the individualized sentencing determination to which he was entitled. Each presented all of the mitigating evidence he chose to produce.","start":4.06,"stop":21.46,"duration":17.4},{"text":"The jury instructions explicitly told the jury to consider each defendant individually.","start":21.46,"stop":28.145,"duration":6.68},{"text":"In fact, there were several separate instructions, some that related only to one defendant or only to another defendant. Each -- the jury for each defendant then had to complete a specific verdict form, and this jury had already proven its ability to distinguish between these two defendants when it convicted one of some counts in the original guilt phase, of which it acquitted the other. The only way the Kansas Supreme Court gets to an Eighth Amendment error in this case -- well, really, there are two points.","start":28.145,"stop":59.94,"duration":31.8},{"text":"One, it relied upon possible, and one instance not even, violations or errors of State law to find a prejudice that -- that rose to an Eighth Amendment level.","start":59.94,"stop":73.05,"duration":13.11},{"text":"And two, it disregarded altogether, with really no explanation, the long-standing foundational principle that juries are presumed to follow their instructions. The two State law errors, arguably, that -- the Kansas Supreme Court found, one was the admission of evidence of the sister who made the comment about Reginald may have told me he shot those people. Well, that's not even an error of State law. They said basically that's prejudicial.","start":73.05,"stop":101.48,"duration":28.43},{"text":"It might not have come in if they had been tried separately, but in fact, that evidence would be relevant to aggravator number 1, that the defendant killed multiple people. That would have been admissible evidence and that -- that just can't be an Eighth Amendment violation.","start":101.48,"stop":115.34,"duration":13.86}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But the Kansas -- the Kansas Court found independent of the severance question that there was constitutional error in the admission of hearsay.","start":115.34,"stop":126.935,"duration":11.6}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the third question presented in the cert position on which the Court has not taken any action yet, Your Honor.","start":126.935,"stop":132.64,"duration":5.7}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":132.64,"stop":132.73,"duration":0.09},{"text":"But when it goes back to Kansas, they can still say thank you for telling us about severance, but we have this other ground that leads to the same bottom line.","start":132.73,"stop":145.015,"duration":12.28}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, and we are certainly hopeful that the Court will take another look at that second question depending on its resolution of the two questions that are in front of it today.","start":145.015,"stop":153.58,"duration":8.57}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But would --","start":153.58,"stop":154.04,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"But if it goes back in that posture, yes, they would have another ground.","start":154.04,"stop":157.095,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Was -- was any evidence introduced with respect to one of the defendants that could not have been introduced against the other had there been severance?","start":157.095,"stop":167.75,"duration":10.66}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"The only arguable evidence really, Justice Kennedy, is the -- what Reginald refers to as the corrupting influence.","start":167.75,"stop":175.925,"duration":8.18},{"text":"But even that, arguably, would be relevant to the mercy consideration to show his character, the nature of this person that is being sentenced. And that was the notion that his mother testified that sometimes -- of course, Jonathan looked up to his big brother, and maybe sometimes Reginald was a bad influence on him.","start":175.925,"stop":195.485,"duration":19.56},{"text":"But that's -- that was really the extent of that evidence.","start":195.485,"stop":198.39,"duration":2.9},{"text":"And that might have come in as a rebuttal to a mercy argument. The Kansas Supreme Court did not really definitively say that was even State law error, but even if you assumed it was --","start":198.39,"stop":208.32,"duration":9.93}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you tell me --","start":208.32,"stop":209.1,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it would only be State law.","start":209.1,"stop":209.79,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"-- what the constitutional standard you're asking us to apply? I -- this argument goes to harmless error; a serious position to take, that even if there was error, no foul -- a foul but no penalty.","start":209.79,"stop":226.245,"duration":16.46},{"text":"Okay? But what standard are we applying? We are not applying the rule -- or are we or should we apply the Rule 14 standard?","start":226.245,"stop":233.96,"duration":7.72}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"No, not -- not for Eighth Amendment purposes, Your Honor.","start":233.96,"stop":237.48,"duration":3.52},{"text":"Kansas would propose -- and I suspect the United States can propose something as well, but it's a very high standard as an Eighth Amendment matter.","start":237.48,"stop":244.44,"duration":6.96},{"text":"And we would say -- we would be content to accept something like it's a serious risk that a defendant will not be able to receive individualized sentencing.","start":244.44,"stop":253.19,"duration":8.75},{"text":"It is sort of molding the traditional notions of joinder with the Eighth Amendment consideration, because that seems to be the only Eighth Amendment consideration here, is the individualized sentencing.","start":253.19,"stop":263.25,"duration":10.06}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it the Eighth Amendment or is it due process?","start":263.25,"stop":264.475,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you could use a due process standard, Justice Scalia, which we would also be fine with.","start":264.475,"stop":268.74,"duration":4.26},{"text":"The question would really be, did joinder so infect the process with unfairness that the proceedings are fundamentally unfair.","start":268.74,"stop":277.465,"duration":8.72}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"That steams like a -- a language that is relevant rather than the cruel and unusual punishments language.","start":277.465,"stop":285.92,"duration":8.46}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, and that's exactly what this Court said in Romano v. Oklahoma, a case in which the defendant's other death sentence in a separate case was admitted against the defendant in the sentencing proceeding.","start":285.92,"stop":297.7,"duration":11.78},{"text":"That sentence later got reversed, and the Oklahoma court said the jury should not have heard about his other sentence as a matter of State law.","start":297.7,"stop":304.83,"duration":7.13},{"text":"That defendant Romano said it is an Eighth Amendment violation, and it's a due process violation. The Court said the Eighth Amendment doesn't have anything to say about what's admissible really.","start":304.83,"stop":315.25,"duration":10.42},{"text":"That is State evidentiary rules, that's not an Eighth Amendment issue. And the Court went on to address the due process claim in Romano, applying that very standard. And as we suggest the Court should do here, one of the things it pointed to specifically was jury instructions that said these are the aggravating circumstances you may consider, you may not consider any others.","start":315.25,"stop":337.155,"duration":21.9},{"text":"The court said we presume the jury follows its instructions, and nothing in the instructions gave the jury here any way to give effect to that improperly admitted evidence. And that's true here to the extent Reginald Carr argues some of this evidence was really used as a nonstatutory aggravating circumstance.","start":337.155,"stop":355.23,"duration":18.08},{"text":"By statute, Kansas does not allow anything other than statutory aggravating circumstances.","start":355.23,"stop":361.51,"duration":6.28},{"text":"In the instructions -- No. 5 I think for Reginald, No. 7 for Jonathan -- very explicitly and clearly say, here are the four aggravating circumstances the State has alleged.","start":361.51,"stop":371.845,"duration":10.34},{"text":"And then the next paragraph, you may not consider anything else as an aggravating circumstance. So in our view, the most the Kansas Supreme Court could come up with is potential violation of State law if, in fact, the evidence which is minimal in the greater scheme of this proceeding that Reginald was a corrupting influence on Jonathan, if that would not have been admitted, that's really all the Kansas Supreme Court is left with to hang its hat on in finding -- in saying there is an Eighth Amendment violation here.","start":371.845,"stop":407.225,"duration":35.38}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you tell me if you're aware, in other States or perhaps even in Kansas in other trials, is it a common practice to sever when there -- for the penalty phase when there are multiple defendants?","start":407.225,"stop":422.1,"duration":14.88}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Kennedy, I think in the briefs -- I do not remember the exact page -- there are two States that mandate severance -- one, Ohio -- and that's, I think, Georgia and Mississippi.","start":422.1,"stop":432.67,"duration":10.57}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"This is just for penalty phase?","start":432.67,"stop":434.195,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it's for the entire proceeding.","start":434.195,"stop":436.66,"duration":2.47},{"text":"And then Ohio, there is a presumption in the favor of severance, but all the other States, there is nothing that mandates or even, I think, creates a presumption of --","start":436.66,"stop":446.33,"duration":9.67}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"It seems it would be very difficult for the trial judge to decide which should go first.","start":446.33,"stop":450.515,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"It would, and that's one of the reasons -- I mean, not just judicial economy but, in a sense, overall fairness --","start":450.515,"stop":456.81,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":456.81,"stop":457.135,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"-- having them tried together and you don't have one defendant having an opportunity to preview the evidence that the State may present and the arguments that may be made.","start":457.135,"stop":465.58,"duration":8.44},{"text":"This Court has recognized that potential tactical advantage in other joinder cases.","start":465.58,"stop":470.42,"duration":4.84},{"text":"Of course, it has not had a joinder capital case like this, but in other circumstances that's a factor. The Court has also emphasized the consistency of determinations with respect to facts.","start":470.42,"stop":481.22,"duration":10.8},{"text":"We are not saying the outcomes have to be the same, but when the evidence, the mitigation evidence is 99 percent overlapping -- they were using the same witnesses, even their experts were co-authors.","start":481.22,"stop":493.47,"duration":12.25},{"text":"They were testifying to the exact same things essentially about each brother. All that overlapping evidence, what this allows is a consistent determination by the jury and evaluation of all that mitigating evidence that leads to whatever outcome the jury decides.","start":493.47,"stop":509.5,"duration":16.03},{"text":"But the jury was very clearly told to consider each defendant individually.","start":509.5,"stop":514.905,"duration":5.4},{"text":"And that's what they got, was individual consideration. I would say also, remember, even if this Court were to think there were some kind of error which Kansas simply does not see here -- again, at most, possibly an error of Kansas law, not an Eighth Amendment violation -- it would have to be harmless under any standard, and Kansas would accept any standard that is beyond a reasonable doubt certainly here.","start":514.905,"stop":543.25,"duration":28.35},{"text":"Given the four uncontested aggravating circumstances --","start":543.25,"stop":547.68,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you'd also have to look -- you have it at the top of your head, maybe forget if you don't, but what I thought I would do is I wanted to look to the aggravating circumstances, what were they.","start":547.68,"stop":560.67,"duration":12.99}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"What were they.","start":560.67,"stop":561.4,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's call it \"he was the monster\" approach.","start":561.4,"stop":563.99,"duration":2.59},{"text":"Reginald was the monster and Jonathan was the puppet or whatever.","start":563.99,"stop":567.785,"duration":3.79},{"text":"I want to look at the aggravators.","start":567.785,"stop":570.02,"duration":2.24},{"text":"I also want to look at the mitigators that Reginald said existed, and then see if this comparative monster, let's call it, fits into any of them. Do you know? Do you know the pages where they are, just by chance?","start":570.02,"stop":584.23,"duration":14.21}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the -- in terms of the -- yes, the aggravating circumstances are set forth in the instructions, Justice Breyer, so --","start":584.23,"stop":592.37,"duration":8.14}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":592.37,"stop":592.78,"duration":0.41},{"text":"I know where they are.","start":592.78,"stop":593.485,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah, Instruction No. 5 for Reginald and Instruction No. 7 for Jonathan, and then following each one, so I believe Instruction No. 6 and Instruction No. 8. But the mitigating -- those are the statutory mitigating circumstances.","start":593.485,"stop":608.45,"duration":14.97},{"text":"So what happens in these cases is the jury is told, here are the statutory. And we list all of them that are listed in the Kansas statute.","start":608.45,"stop":615.75,"duration":7.3},{"text":"And then you can --","start":615.75,"stop":616.47,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"On what page do you list them?","start":616.47,"stop":618.02,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, so those are listed in Instruction No. 6 and Instruction No. 8.","start":618.02,"stop":623.07,"duration":5.05},{"text":"It's all in the petition --","start":623.07,"stop":623.97,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"If, in fact, this gets in, then I guess what I have to do is go through this huge record on the sentencing anyway and see do I really think that this evidence that came in that the younger one thought the older one was the monster, et cetera, did it really have an effect?","start":623.97,"stop":642.42,"duration":18.45}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":642.42,"stop":643.29,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I would have to do.","start":643.29,"stop":644.2,"duration":0.91},{"text":"I don't see how I could avoid that if they are at all relevant.","start":644.2,"stop":646.695,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say, first of all, if were you to do that, it would be quite clear. The evidence is overwhelming. But furthermore, the premise is not supported really by the record.","start":646.695,"stop":655.9,"duration":9.2},{"text":"They say Jonathan's whole strategy was to paint Reginald as the bad actor here.","start":655.9,"stop":661.535,"duration":5.63},{"text":"That's not really what happened.","start":661.535,"stop":663.555,"duration":2.02},{"text":"What they both presented was lots of witnesses and testimony about their -- their childhood and their experiences growing up, and they presented psychological experts to talk about their mental condition.","start":663.555,"stop":673.805,"duration":10.25},{"text":"No expert said Reginald had some kind of psychological control over Jonathan. That -- that testimony, to the extent it's there at all, comes from their mother.","start":673.805,"stop":682.75,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"But what do you think about a case, whether or not this is that case, in which it is quite clear to a judge that each of two defendants is just going to be pointing to the other person and saying, that was the bad actor.","start":682.75,"stop":697.955,"duration":15.21},{"text":"He is why these terrible crimes committed.","start":697.955,"stop":700.87,"duration":2.91},{"text":"And you know that -- you know, each of them is going to be doing that. Should a judge separate the penalty proceeding in that context?","start":700.87,"stop":708.25,"duration":7.38}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, not necessarily.","start":708.25,"stop":709.86,"duration":1.61},{"text":"If the high standard is met that it will not be possible, perhaps, to give individualized consideration to each in an Eighth Amendment or a due process standard is going to be so fundamentally unfair, if you can meet that very high standard, then -- but that's always been the Court's approach.","start":709.86,"stop":724.63,"duration":14.77},{"text":"It is a case-by-case determination. Even Zafiro, which is a joinder case --","start":724.63,"stop":728.9,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I guess I am asking you in what kind of factual circumstances you would find that standard met?","start":728.9,"stop":734.065,"duration":5.17}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Rarely, but I think it would be -- certainly the Court has recognized in Bruton, you have some sort of co-defendant confession -- I mean, confession situations, if there was something that had not been used in the guilt phase, might be relevant in the sentencing.","start":734.065,"stop":747.77,"duration":13.7},{"text":"That might be so prejudicial. We have tried to think of other examples.","start":747.77,"stop":752.01,"duration":4.24},{"text":"I might suggest something like one is claiming at that point in time some kind of insanity, even though they didn't succeed on that at trial.","start":752.01,"stop":759.18,"duration":7.17},{"text":"If there was something really starkly contradictory in their presentations and you were going to get a lot of evidence about one that really had nothing to do at all with the other. But we do believe it's a high standard that would rarely be satisfied, especially given the Court's long-standing presumption that the jury follows its instructions.","start":759.18,"stop":779.69,"duration":20.51},{"text":"And that's one thing I would point out here, the complaints that each makes in this Court. First of all, at least one of those complaints really wasn't even made in the Kansas Supreme Court, much less the trial court, and that's the shackling of Reginald and whether that might have prejudiced Jonathan. But they -- there was no complaints during the sentencing proceeding.","start":779.69,"stop":800.495,"duration":20.8},{"text":"This corrupting influence evidence is relevant only for Jonathan's mitigation case, not with respect to Reginald; can we have a limiting instruction? Reginald has anti-social personality disorder; there was no request for any sort of limiting that that -- that's not applicable to Jonathan.","start":800.495,"stop":818.59,"duration":18.1},{"text":"Although, of course, the irony there is that Jonathan's own expert all but diagnosed him as anti-social personality.","start":818.59,"stop":826.55,"duration":7.96},{"text":"He said out of 26 risk factors that the Department of Justice has recognized for violence and sexual violence, Jonathan has 24 of them. And both brothers talked about family history of mental illness.","start":826.55,"stop":838.91,"duration":12.36},{"text":"Both brothers and their experts talked about whether some of these things were hereditary or genetic.","start":838.91,"stop":843.77,"duration":4.86},{"text":"This was really a case in which it made very good sense to proceed with a joint proceeding, because the evidence, 99 percent was overlapping, essentially.","start":843.77,"stop":856.24,"duration":12.47},{"text":"I mean, they were calling the same witnesses, taking turns with those witnesses. Judicial economy nor fairness, neither one would have been served any better by separating this into two proceedings. And, in fact, I will conclude for now, unless there are further questions, with this observation, that prior to trial, to the guilt phase, the prosecution actually offered to have two juries sit through this proceeding.","start":856.24,"stop":882.215,"duration":25.98},{"text":"Jonathan's attorney said he would consider it, and Reginald's attorney rejected it. So the State even tried to -- to agree to some workable system and -- and it was declined. So unless there are further questions, I will reserve the remainder of my time.","start":882.215,"stop":898.16,"duration":15.94}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel. Ms. Kovner.","start":898.16,"stop":926.15,"duration":27.99}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: The Kansas Supreme Court erred when it found that the State violated the Eighth Amendment by conducting joint sentencing proceedings for the crimes the Respondents committed together.","start":926.15,"stop":937.71,"duration":11.56},{"text":"Joint proceedings can enhance accuracy and fairness, as a long line of this Court's cases hold.","start":937.71,"stop":942.875,"duration":5.16},{"text":"They provide a fuller evidentiary record to juries that are assessing relative culpability, and they prevent arbitrary disparities that may arise when two juries reach inconsistent conclusions about the common facts of a single crime.","start":942.875,"stop":955.595,"duration":12.72}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Ms. Kovner, is there any difference between the Federal government's position and the position of the State of Kansas on this question?","start":955.595,"stop":962.79,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"As to the standard, I think there's a small difference.","start":962.79,"stop":965.685,"duration":2.89},{"text":"I think our proposal is that the constitutional standard is whether evidence or argument resulted in a denial of due process or the deprivation of an individualized sentencing proceeding. And that's slightly different from Kansas's standard, because Kansas is proposing a rule that involves analysis of risk, and we think that is part of the statutory rule under Rule 14, as Justice Sotomayor alluded to.","start":965.685,"stop":988.25,"duration":22.57},{"text":"It's also part of the statutory standard that states \"by and large are applying,\" but we think the constitutional question is just, was this person deprived of a fair trial by the evidence that came in? And that's the constitutional question.","start":988.25,"stop":1000.22,"duration":11.97}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"When you said it the first time, you had \"deprived of a fair trial\" and then something about individualized sentencing; is that right? Is that supposed to indicate that this is deriving both from the Due Process Clause and from the Eighth Amendment?","start":1000.22,"stop":1011.99,"duration":11.77}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Eighth Amendment does speak to this need for an individualized sentencing determination.","start":1011.99,"stop":1016.8,"duration":4.81},{"text":"We would think that the Due Process Clause also requires that proceedings be individualized. But we would agree that if there were a situation where there was a joint trial and because of the evidence introduced by one, for instance, a jury simply could not give individualized consideration to a second -- second defendant, that would be a constitutional problem. And to give an example of that -- I mean, I think the example the Court suggests in Zafiro of that is where there is aggravating evidence that pertains only to one defendant, but that that aggravating evidence is just so prejudicial and so overpowering that the jury couldn't really separate the two and would be inclined to sort of judge the second one by association. So I think that's the example the Court gives in Zafiro.","start":1016.8,"stop":1057.14,"duration":40.34},{"text":"But it's not --","start":1057.14,"stop":1057.9,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Don't you think individualized consideration is required even in the non-capital cases?","start":1057.9,"stop":1065.465,"duration":7.56}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely, Your Honor.","start":1065.465,"stop":1066.47,"duration":1.01},{"text":"So I think --","start":1066.47,"stop":1066.96,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"It's really a due process consideration, isn't it?","start":1066.96,"stop":1069.77,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"I think due process encompasses that requirement of individualized consideration. Just to address several of the points that came up during Petitioner's argument, I think -- as to the question that Justice Kagan asked about whether, when defendants are simply pointing the finger at each other, that would necessitate severance.","start":1069.77,"stop":1089.44,"duration":19.67},{"text":"I think that's the question that the Court addressed in Zafiro, where that was essentially the claim the defendants were making, that we're both going to point the finger at each other at trial.","start":1089.44,"stop":1097.065,"duration":7.63},{"text":"And the Court said that doesn't necessitate severance; that that may, in fact, increase the jury's ability to reach an accurate verdict, to reach an accurate assessment of relative culpability, and enhance fairness.","start":1097.065,"stop":1108.265,"duration":11.2},{"text":"So we don't think that that's a situation that would require severance.","start":1108.265,"stop":1111.115,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I guess the strongest evidence for Reginald is Temica's testimony. It's -- it's pretty prejudicial.","start":1111.115,"stop":1121.58,"duration":10.46},{"text":"She said he's -- he's the one who -- he said he's the one who shot.","start":1121.58,"stop":1125.429,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think that that's prejudicial evidence, certainly not any constitutional problem with the admission of that evidence.","start":1125.429,"stop":1131.705,"duration":6.28},{"text":"I don't think that even Reginald Carr is asserting that that evidence couldn't have come in against him.","start":1131.705,"stop":1136.97,"duration":5.27},{"text":"Rather he is asserting or the State below suggested -- the State court below suggested maybe that -- maybe the State didn't know about that evidence, and maybe just as a factual matter it wouldn't have come in. But there's no constitutional unfairness with evidence coming in on a co-defendant's case that's harmful but accurate as to you.","start":1136.97,"stop":1153.99,"duration":17.02},{"text":"That's something the Court said in -- in Zafiro.","start":1153.99,"stop":1156.13,"duration":2.14},{"text":"If it's accurate and relevant evidence that comes in on a co-defendant's case, there's no constitutional unfairness as to you. I think Reginald's primary claim before this Court is that there was a violation of State evidentiary law because some of the other evidence, the evidence of bad influence, might not have come in under the State rules.","start":1156.13,"stop":1175.025,"duration":18.89},{"text":"I think this Court's cases are clear that a violation of State evidentiary law is simply a matter of State law.","start":1175.025,"stop":1180.545,"duration":5.52},{"text":"The State could decide that necessitates reversal, but it's not a constitutional error.","start":1180.545,"stop":1184.805,"duration":4.26},{"text":"That's what this Court said in Romano.","start":1184.805,"stop":1185.93,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"It would depend on what is was, wouldn't it? I mean, so I'm still asking the same question.","start":1185.93,"stop":1192.265,"duration":6.34},{"text":"If the -- I take it that Reginald could not have introduced evidence refuting these brothers' state of mind that he was the monster.","start":1192.265,"stop":1204.755,"duration":12.49},{"text":"That's what you're referring to by the bad influence. So the jury might have taken that evidence into account in trying to decide whether Reginald, for other reasons than in the statute, was a sympathetic enough character not to provide the death penalty. That's conceivable. But severance is very, very rare, and joint trials are very common.","start":1204.755,"stop":1227.36,"duration":22.6},{"text":"And very common is the claim on an appeal in any kind of a case that it shouldn't -- it should have been severed. So do you have cases that you can think of that would be good precedent for you where a court, including particularly this Court, said, of course there might be a little prejudice here, some, but it's not enough to warrant severance? Because I think what I have to do is read the record on this point, and then I need something to compare it with.","start":1227.36,"stop":1255.235,"duration":27.88}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I want to go back -- I'd like to answer the question and then go back to the premise --","start":1255.235,"stop":1259.09,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1259.09,"stop":1259.22,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"-- because I am not sure I agree with the premise. But as to whether any prejudice is a problem, I think the best case for us is Zafiro.","start":1259.22,"stop":1265.685,"duration":6.46},{"text":"Zafiro talks about the idea that what you need -- that joinder is presumably going to enhance fairness and accuracy. And what you need is substantial prejudice, even to have a statutory problem, and then -- even then we are going to presume that a limiting instruction would be sufficient to cure it. So that would be our best case on that point. But, Your Honor, I think the inquiry under the Eighth Amendment has to be would the Constitution have prohibited this evidence from coming in as to Reginald Carr.","start":1265.685,"stop":1289.845,"duration":24.16},{"text":"And we think the answer is no.","start":1289.845,"stop":1292.46,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Any evidence that's relevant to an individual defendant --","start":1292.46,"stop":1294.55,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, normally in severance cases, forgetting the death cases, seems to me the argument has been, look, they never would have gotten this piece of evidence in against my client.","start":1294.55,"stop":1305.39,"duration":10.84},{"text":"They brought it in against the other client.","start":1305.39,"stop":1307.755,"duration":2.37},{"text":"Now, go look at that evidence and you'll see how much my prejudice -- that my client was prejudiced by that. I do not know whether you call that due process.","start":1307.755,"stop":1316.69,"duration":8.93},{"text":"Maybe you do.","start":1316.69,"stop":1317.83,"duration":1.14},{"text":"But that's the kind of argument which seems for a quantitative weighing.","start":1317.83,"stop":1322.295,"duration":4.47},{"text":"That's why I asked the question.","start":1322.295,"stop":1324.49,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"I think I would go back to Zafiro again on that one, Your Honor, because I think Zafiro establishes that when accurate evidence comes in through a co-defendant that is relative -- that's relevant to the jury's determination, that's not prejudice.","start":1324.49,"stop":1336.905,"duration":12.41},{"text":"That's information that may enhance the accuracy of what the jury --","start":1336.905,"stop":1339.93,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you tell me why we should apply the Zafiro standard, which was joint trials, but this is joint sentencing where there is a different -- why there should be exactly the same standard applied?","start":1339.93,"stop":1354.63,"duration":14.7}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"So we think Zafiro --","start":1354.63,"stop":1355.71,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you need individualized sentencing? So can't you say, or aren't you required to say that something a little bit more than -- than the efficiency of a joint trial has to compel --","start":1355.71,"stop":1371.26,"duration":15.55}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1371.26,"stop":1372.77,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"-- has to be considered?","start":1372.77,"stop":1373.91,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1373.91,"stop":1374.7,"duration":0.79},{"text":"We agree that sentencings may involve special considerations.","start":1374.7,"stop":1378.7,"duration":4},{"text":"What we think Zafiro establishes is that generally when more relevant information is placed before a jury, that's not prejudice to a defendant, that's not unfair, and that juries with more information are likely to make more accurate decisions, and we think that's equally true at sentencing. And, similarly, that juries with more -- who are confronted with two defendants together can avoid the unwarranted disparities that may occur when juries reach different results -- two different juries considering the same facts reach different results on those facts.","start":1378.7,"stop":1404.47,"duration":25.77},{"text":"And that's equally true at sentencing.","start":1404.47,"stop":1405.69,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Sorry, but I'm not --","start":1405.69,"stop":1406.3,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you would need two -- two separate juries, wouldn't you? I mean --","start":1406.3,"stop":1409.175,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's what the Kansas Supreme Court said here.","start":1409.175,"stop":1411.75,"duration":2.58},{"text":"And the result of that is -- is going to be that two different juries confronted with the very same aggravating circumstances in largely parallel mitigation cases may simply weigh factors like mercy differently.","start":1411.75,"stop":1423.685,"duration":11.93}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But wouldn't -- wouldn't the second jury have to know the facts relevant to mitigation, as well as aggravation, I suppose, that came out in the main trial?","start":1423.685,"stop":1433.73,"duration":10.05}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"It's -- it's certainly possible, Your Honor, that if there was a second jury, the government could simply introduce, for instance, the evidence of Reginald Carr's statement to his sister at the second trial.","start":1433.73,"stop":1444,"duration":10.27},{"text":"So you're introducing this disparity that Justice Kennedy alluded to between the defendant who goes first and the defendant who goes second.","start":1444,"stop":1448.67,"duration":4.67}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would this second jury have been present for the -- for the guilt phase?","start":1448.67,"stop":1452.665,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in -- in the Federal system, there are a number of ways you could do it. Could you have two juries that hear both the guilt phase and -- and the penalty phase.","start":1452.665,"stop":1464.065,"duration":11.4},{"text":"You could have a second jury impanelled only for the -- the penalty phase.","start":1464.065,"stop":1469.33,"duration":5.26},{"text":"But then in a case like this, you would need to essentially repeat all the trial evidence, including calling victims again, because that -- because the State was relying on its evidence from the trial phase, and that is generally, we submit, going to be the case.","start":1469.33,"stop":1480.49,"duration":11.16}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I think I missed something you said, but -- forgive me.","start":1480.49,"stop":1482.53,"duration":2.04},{"text":"But the constitutional standard that you're proposing, is that a constitutional standard for both the guilt phase and the sentencing phase? And is it also for both non-capital and capital? Are you drawing no distinctions among those four things?","start":1482.53,"stop":1499.815,"duration":17.29}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's right, Your Honor.","start":1499.815,"stop":1501.13,"duration":1.32},{"text":"I mean, that -- because we think that the due process standard essentially subsumes the requirement of individualized consideration, and, of course, due process is applicable at the trial phase and at the sentencing phase in capital and non-capital trials.","start":1501.13,"stop":1512.745,"duration":11.61}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"So it seems a little bit counterintuitive to me, the idea that, you know, the guilt phase in a very minor crime would have the exact same standard applicable to it as the guilt phase of a capital crime and then as the sentencing phase of a capital crime.","start":1512.745,"stop":1528.91,"duration":16.17}]},{"speakerName":"Rachel P. Kovner","textObjs":[{"text":"If I may answer really briefly? Your Honor, we think the reason that's the case is that joint trials often enhance accuracy and fairness.","start":1528.91,"stop":1536.64,"duration":7.73},{"text":"So we agree that accuracy and fairness considerations are at their paramount in capital cases, but we do not think that militates for a different standard in capital cases because we think that the standard that the courts are applying is one that's going to generally enhance those values.","start":1536.64,"stop":1550.19,"duration":13.55}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel. Mr. Liu.","start":1550.19,"stop":1557.52,"duration":7.33}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may please the Court: I want to begin by emphasizing how narrow our rule is.","start":1557.52,"stop":1563.69,"duration":6.17},{"text":"Justice Kagan asked the question involving a -- a case where the two defendants pointed their fingers at each other.","start":1563.69,"stop":1569.735,"duration":6.04},{"text":"We are not advocating a rule that would require severance in any case where two defendants point their fingers at -- at each other. We are advocating a rule that this Court has recognized in Zant, Stringer, in Sanders, that -- that an Eighth Amendment violation occurs when the weighing process itself is skewed.","start":1569.735,"stop":1587.95,"duration":18.22},{"text":"And the weighing --","start":1587.95,"stop":1588.91,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But are you saying the severance rule is the same in non-capital as in capital cases?","start":1588.91,"stop":1596.08,"duration":7.17}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"The general severance rule, Your Honor, is the same.","start":1596.08,"stop":1598.83,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And you just look for prejudice?","start":1598.83,"stop":1600.31,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1600.31,"stop":1600.98,"duration":0.67},{"text":"The general rule is you can't have severance when it would compromise someone's constitutional rights.","start":1600.98,"stop":1606.09,"duration":5.11},{"text":"The right at issue here just happens to be an Eighth Amendment right, but we are not advocating an Eighth Amendment rule that would apply beyond the capital context or even beyond the penalty phase.","start":1606.09,"stop":1615.92,"duration":9.83},{"text":"That's --","start":1615.92,"stop":1616.445,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You know, if you violated an individualized sentence, why would we apply harmless error review? Meaning, it seems counterintuitive.","start":1616.445,"stop":1629.54,"duration":13.1},{"text":"We are now becoming the sentencing -- the sentencing body.","start":1629.54,"stop":1632.735,"duration":3.19},{"text":"No?","start":1632.735,"stop":1633.275,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely.","start":1633.275,"stop":1634.18,"duration":0.9},{"text":"And I think --","start":1634.18,"stop":1634.93,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, so then we have to do the -- in harmless error, we have to decide whether the aggravators outweighed the mitigators, et cetera, so much that none of the error could have affected that choice?","start":1634.93,"stop":1648.92,"duration":13.99}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this Court, Your Honor, recognized in Satterwhite precisely how difficult it would be to conduct a harmless error analysis in a penalty phase, and that's precisely because there are so many factors involved. Sure, the crimes in the case were horrific, but that's just one side of the scale in a harmless error inquiry.","start":1648.92,"stop":1666.42,"duration":17.5},{"text":"There is an entire other side of the balance, the mitigation side.","start":1666.42,"stop":1670.005,"duration":3.59},{"text":"And so it is quite difficult for this Court, on a cold record, to go through the harmless error analysis.","start":1670.005,"stop":1676.35,"duration":6.34}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"We have to do it, though, right? I mean, that's -- that's part of -- part of our jurisprudence. So what -- what do you think are the -- are -- are the factors that would suggest the jury would have come out a different way had the rule that you urge been adopted? What -- what specifically? One is the shackling of the -- of the co-defendant?","start":1676.35,"stop":1699.59,"duration":23.24}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we are not representing Reginald Carr.","start":1699.59,"stop":1702.35,"duration":2.76},{"text":"We're not basing our claim around the shackling.","start":1702.35,"stop":1705.02,"duration":2.67},{"text":"Our -- our claim revolves around the evidence that Jonathan presented that Reginald had a corrupting influence on him while they were growing up. And that evidence, as the Kansas Supreme Court itself held at Petition Appendix 411, falls beyond the rubric of any valid sentencing factor.","start":1705.02,"stop":1722.715,"duration":17.69}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"But, Mr. Liu, I mean, given the kind of evidence that was presented in this case, the idea that somebody was a lousy big brother seems pretty small on -- in the -- in the scale of things.","start":1722.715,"stop":1737.39,"duration":14.68}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, a few responses to that.","start":1737.39,"stop":1738.7,"duration":1.31},{"text":"To begin with, I think Your -- Your Honor is understating the evidence here.","start":1738.7,"stop":1742.74,"duration":4.04},{"text":"This wasn't just that Reginald was a lousy big brother.","start":1742.74,"stop":1746.02,"duration":3.28},{"text":"It was that he did things to Jonathan that turned Jonathan into the person who was capable of committing and even leading these crimes.","start":1746.02,"stop":1753.44,"duration":7.42},{"text":"So this wasn't just \"lousy big brother\" evidence, this was evidence that Reginald himself was the source of what caused Jonathan to do the things he did. But, Your Honor, I think it's also important to keep in mind two separate parts of the inquiry; there is the violation and the harmless error analysis.","start":1753.44,"stop":1769.4,"duration":15.96},{"text":"And this Court said in Stringer that even a thumb on the scales is enough to skew the weighing process in violation of the Eighth Amendment.","start":1769.4,"stop":1776.565,"duration":7.16}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But what -- what evidence that shouldn't have been admitted wouldn't have been admitted in the -- in the separate trial?","start":1776.565,"stop":1785.57,"duration":9}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, all this evidence, Mr. Chief Justice, that says Reginald was a corrupting influence on his brother, that wouldn't have come in in a separate trial for two reasons: Number one, as the Kansas Supreme Court held at Petition Appendix 411, that evidence was improper, nonstatutory, aggravating evidence, which is to say, all the aggravating factors before the prosecution pursuit in this case all had to do with the circumstances of the crime. But this evidence had nothing to do with the circumstances of what happened on December 15th, it had to do with the defendant's character concerning circumstances that occurred years, even decades, before the crimes at issue.","start":1785.57,"stop":1822.9,"duration":37.33}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, wait a minute. You're -- you're representing the brother who was the alleged corrupting influence, right?","start":1822.9,"stop":1829.7,"duration":6.8}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, the corruptor.","start":1829.7,"stop":1831.18,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"The corruptor was sentenced, by the same jury, to death.","start":1831.18,"stop":1837.135,"duration":5.95},{"text":"So how could it possibly be that without the corrupting action of your client, the jury would have sentenced your client to life even though the corruptee was sentenced to death? That doesn't seem to me at all likely.","start":1837.135,"stop":1856.375,"duration":19.24}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, to begin -- begin with, I don't think Jonathan Carr's sentence is a proper baseline to use.","start":1856.375,"stop":1861.42,"duration":5.05},{"text":"As my friend will argue in a few minute, his own sentence was prejudiced by severance. But even moving beyond that, there is every reason to believe that the jury viewed Jonathan as overall more culpable than Reginald.","start":1861.42,"stop":1873.475,"duration":12.05},{"text":"After all, the State never established who the shooter was here.","start":1873.475,"stop":1876.54,"duration":3.07},{"text":"If the jury believed that Jonathan was the shooter, the jury could have believed that Jonathan was so culpable that even with his evidence that he had been corrupted by Reginald, it would have given a life sentence.","start":1876.54,"stop":1888.09,"duration":11.55},{"text":"I think --","start":1888.09,"stop":1888.44,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me -- let me put the crime to you.","start":1888.44,"stop":1891.31,"duration":2.87},{"text":"You tell me which of these descriptions of the -- of the crime are -- are incorrect.","start":1891.31,"stop":1900.325,"duration":9.02},{"text":"These two men broke into a house in which there were three men and two women.","start":1900.325,"stop":1908.99,"duration":8.66},{"text":"They ordered the five to remove their clothes, forced them into a closet.","start":1908.99,"stop":1915.62,"duration":6.63},{"text":"Over the course of three hours, they demanded that the two women perform various sexual acts on one another.","start":1915.62,"stop":1922.355,"duration":6.74},{"text":"They demanded at gunpoint that each of the three men have sexual intercourse with both women. Then Reginald drove the victims one by one to various ATMs to withdraw cash.","start":1922.355,"stop":1934.445,"duration":12.09},{"text":"Jonathan raped or attempted to rape both women twice, and Reginald raped Holly G., who later testified, once.","start":1934.445,"stop":1943.585,"duration":9.14},{"text":"Placing the three men, still naked, in the trunk of one of their cars, the cars drove all five to a soccer field, forced them to kneel in the snow, and shot them execution-style in the back of the head. One of them, fortuitously, was not killed because -- I think it was a hair clip that she was wearing deflected the bullet.","start":1943.585,"stop":1965.925,"duration":22.34},{"text":"And she is the one who testified to all of this activity. And you truly think -- oh, and they ran over her too.","start":1965.925,"stop":1977.42,"duration":11.5},{"text":"After shooting her in the head, the car ran over her. You truly think that this jury, but for the fact that your client was a corruptor, would not have imposed the death penalty?","start":1977.42,"stop":1991.325,"duration":13.9}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"We do, Justice Scalia.","start":1991.325,"stop":1992.75,"duration":1.42},{"text":"In your own opinion in last term in Glossip, you noted that the egregiousness of an offense is just one factor in determining whether a sentence is appropriate at the penalty phase.","start":1992.75,"stop":2003.125,"duration":10.38},{"text":"And Reginald Carr submitted a week and a half full of mitigation evidence that extenuated this offense. So I don't -- I think when you -- when you take all that all into account and consider the fact that this wasn't an easy case for the jury -- the jury, after all, deliberated a full day on what the -- what Kansas thinks is quite an easy case. I think the -- the scales of the weighing process were much more evenly balanced than that.","start":2003.125,"stop":2029.535,"duration":26.41}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think that the desire to spare Holly from having to testify more than once is a relevant factor here? And if so, how could that be -- how do you -- how would you propose to accommodate them?","start":2029.535,"stop":2043,"duration":13.46}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not a relevant factor and that's not my saying it, it's this Court saying it. This Court in Zafiro and Bruton has said that the benefits of joinder, while they may exist, cannot come at the price of constitutional rights. So while I -- I completely appreciate that severance would require some duplication of resources, that's precisely the sort of benefit that this Court has said cannot trump the Eighth Amendment.","start":2043,"stop":2070.51,"duration":27.51}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So if you're right, joinder being among the most common kind of thing that gangs and drugs and so forth, why won't the same argument be made over and over preventing -- requiring severance in dozens and dozens, perhaps hundreds of cases where the government tries people together? Because they will say there are different relationships among members of the gang.","start":2070.51,"stop":2092.25,"duration":21.74},{"text":"Those relationships -- some evidence would come in that would negative the relationship that would tend to show that this particular individual wasn't actually involved in this aspect of it, et cetera. That's why my experience on the Courts, lower courts particularly, leads me to think it's a very rarely accepted argument, severance.","start":2092.25,"stop":2110.51,"duration":18.26}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you're right, Justice Breyer --","start":2110.51,"stop":2111.83,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's why I'm interested in -- I mean because if it would, you'd find it very unusual to try people together, which, in fact, is very usual.","start":2111.83,"stop":2120.085,"duration":8.26},{"text":"And so when you told me there is no separate thing for the death cases, then I imagine it would affect every criminal trial of gangs throughout the country.","start":2120.085,"stop":2128.935,"duration":8.85}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think --","start":2128.935,"stop":2129.65,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And that is something that's concerning me and I am looking for an answer.","start":2129.65,"stop":2133.135,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"You're absolutely right, Justice Breyer, that under our rule, the circumstances of each case are relevant.","start":2133.135,"stop":2139.13,"duration":5.99},{"text":"But I think what's also important is -- is that some -- the circumstances of some cases might not give rise for severance.","start":2139.13,"stop":2146.21,"duration":7.08}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I'm looking for.","start":2146.21,"stop":2147.66,"duration":1.45},{"text":"Why is it you believe that if I were to decide in your favor on this case and find the sufficient prejudice to warrant severance here, I wouldn't at the same time be throwing a huge monkey wrench --","start":2147.66,"stop":2160.075,"duration":12.41}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2160.075,"stop":2160.615,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- into the ordinary cases of gangs, drugs, et cetera, where joinder is very common and reversal is very rare.","start":2160.615,"stop":2169.885,"duration":9.27}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the evidence here is special in the sense that it fell beyond any existing sentencing factor.","start":2169.885,"stop":2177.06,"duration":7.17}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you proposing just separate sentencing hearings, or are you proposing separate juries for each of the brothers?","start":2177.06,"stop":2188.45,"duration":11.39}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Kansas Supreme Court in this case ordered as its remedy a new trial with two juries, but I don't think that is necessarily going to be the required remedy in every case.","start":2188.45,"stop":2199.95,"duration":11.5},{"text":"There are different ways, Justice Ginsburg, to solve the problems of sentencing.","start":2199.95,"stop":2204.09,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's take this case.","start":2204.09,"stop":2205.3,"duration":1.21},{"text":"If you had only one jury and Jonathan goes first, that jury, when it gets to Reginald's case, is not going to forget everything it heard in Jonathan's case.","start":2205.3,"stop":2221.375,"duration":16.07}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"You're absolutely right, Justice Ginsburg.","start":2221.375,"stop":2223.59,"duration":2.22},{"text":"I don't think a sequential solution with Jonathan going first is going to work in this case precisely because the jury won't -- you won't be able to unring the bell of the -- precisely the evidence we think is prejudicial in this case.","start":2223.59,"stop":2239.36,"duration":15.77},{"text":"But that's not to say that a sequential solution isn't going to work in the mine run of cases. This case is special just because there -- there is some allegation that the prejudice ran both ways.","start":2239.36,"stop":2250.59,"duration":11.23}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But the minute -- but the minute you defend the idea of two different juries, then you sacrifice the desirability and the possibility of consistency.","start":2250.59,"stop":2261.82,"duration":11.23}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Justice Kennedy, there are many ways that States have developed to resolve the problem of inconsistent verdicts among different juries. One way is what the Georgia State has done, which is had proportionality review.","start":2261.82,"stop":2275.04,"duration":13.22},{"text":"They ask the appellate courts to look across many sentences to see if they are inconsistent. Another way the Federal government has a solution to this, is that let one jury know how the other jury sentenced the other defendant.","start":2275.04,"stop":2288.08,"duration":13.04},{"text":"That's 18 U.S.C. 3592(a)(4)","start":2288.08,"stop":2292.06,"duration":3.98},{"text":"And so there are ways to solve the problem of inconsistent verdicts across juries.","start":2292.06,"stop":2296.54,"duration":4.48},{"text":"But what's --","start":2296.54,"stop":2297.07,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That sounds -- that sounds pretty prejudicial to me.","start":2297.07,"stop":2299.805,"duration":2.73},{"text":"If the second case, you say, oh, the jury considered this and individual circumstances, you know, these people act together, and by the way, a jury of your peers unanimously found beyond a reasonable doubt that this guy should be sentenced to death; now do whatever you want with this guy.","start":2299.805,"stop":2314.075,"duration":14.27},{"text":"That sounds pretty prejudicial to me.","start":2314.075,"stop":2317.075,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's -- it's -- if you think that is prejudicial, Mr. Chief Justice, then this proceeding was quite prejudicial too because the jury was asked to make that same exact comparison. But the specific prejudice we are alleging here is -- is unique to these or at least quite -- quite restricted to the circumstances of this case.","start":2317.075,"stop":2338.53,"duration":21.46}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Liu, could you, for me, just tell me what is the specific prejudice you're alleging here? In other words, tell me more than just, oh, he was a corrupting influence.","start":2338.53,"stop":2348.33,"duration":9.8},{"text":"What evidence particularly came in --","start":2348.33,"stop":2350.96,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure.","start":2350.96,"stop":2351.25,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and why do you think it might have mattered to the jury? Just give me your best shot.","start":2351.25,"stop":2355.91,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure.","start":2355.91,"stop":2356.595,"duration":0.68},{"text":"Well, Kansas said there was no expert testimony on this, but that's wrong. Dr. Cunningham, at Joint Appendix pages 324 to 329, explained how Jonathan looked up to Reggie, and every time they would get together they would do drugs heavily together, that when -- that when they were ages 6 or 7, Reginald prompted someone to have sex with Jonathan. These are precisely the sort of evidence that shows that however bad you think Jonathan is, Reginald is worse because Reginald is the one who created the person Jonathan is. It's in a sense making Reginald doubly culpable for these offenses; that, well, whatever you think Jonathan did -- and yes, as Justice Scalia read, there were some horrific things done -- well, Reginald should be punished for not only everything Reginald did, but also everything Jonathan did. So this is precisely the sort of evidence that basically transfers all of Jonathan's actions to Reginald.","start":2356.595,"stop":2420.43,"duration":63.84},{"text":"And that's why it's so prejudicial when you get in the jury room, it's because it -- it skews the weighing process. And a skewing of the weighing process is an error this Court has recognized for 30 years.","start":2420.43,"stop":2432.99,"duration":12.56},{"text":"This isn't something that we -- we came up special for this case.","start":2432.99,"stop":2436.555,"duration":3.57},{"text":"This Court has recognized time and again that when a jury is told to consider an improper element in the weighing process, the weighing process is therefore skewed.","start":2436.555,"stop":2446.56,"duration":10.01},{"text":"And the only thing that can cure that error is either harmless error review or --","start":2446.56,"stop":2450.85,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But it --","start":2450.85,"stop":2451.04,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"-- reweighing by the State court.","start":2451.04,"stop":2452.21,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But it has to have been harmless inasmuch as the person who was influenced by your client also got the death penalty.","start":2452.21,"stop":2461.82,"duration":9.61},{"text":"How can you say that what made the difference was the fact that your client was a corrupting influence upon his younger brother?","start":2461.82,"stop":2470.595,"duration":8.77}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Justice Scalia, the State never established the identity of the shooter, and that is the key horrific act in this case.","start":2470.595,"stop":2478.17,"duration":7.58},{"text":"If the jury believed Jonathan was the shooter, then the jury might have given him the death penalty anyway regardless of what Reginald did to him.","start":2478.17,"stop":2486.71,"duration":8.54}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I doubt whether that is the key.","start":2486.71,"stop":2488.795,"duration":2.09},{"text":"You really think that that's the only thing the jury is going to be focused on, is who pulled the trigger? My Lord.","start":2488.795,"stop":2496.84,"duration":8.05}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think it's the only -- I don't think it's the only thing, but it's certainly the main thing given that we are here on a capital murder charge.","start":2496.84,"stop":2504.325,"duration":7.48}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think that on a retrial they cannot use the sister to prove that Reginald claimed he was the shooter?","start":2504.325,"stop":2512.6,"duration":8.28}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2512.6,"stop":2513.11,"duration":0.51},{"text":"And I think that just highlights exactly how narrow our rule is.","start":2513.11,"stop":2517.135,"duration":4.03},{"text":"That the evidence that Temica said that Reginald told her that Reginald was the shooter goes to the circumstances of the crime.","start":2517.135,"stop":2525.01,"duration":7.88},{"text":"And that sort of finger pointing, who shot who on the day of the crime, is going to fall comfortably within an existing sentencing factor, and as a result, is not going to skew the weighing process.","start":2525.01,"stop":2536.81,"duration":11.8}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So the only issue you think was prejudicial was that he was a corruptor?","start":2536.81,"stop":2541.735,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely.","start":2541.735,"stop":2542.4,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"The evidence.","start":2542.4,"stop":2543.13,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"And for reasons I -- I gave to Justice Kagan, that evidence was extremely prejudicial. It skewed the weighing process because it transferred Jonathan's culpability back onto Reginald's shoulders. If I may, I'd just like to address a few points raised by my friend from Kansas.","start":2543.13,"stop":2563.23,"duration":20.1},{"text":"He said the instructions solve the problem.","start":2563.23,"stop":2566.91,"duration":3.68},{"text":"Well, none of the instructions told the jury to consider this evidence about the corrupting influence only as to Jonathan. Now, on the contrary, the instructions -- Instruction No. 2 told the jury consider the evidence applicable to each defendant.","start":2566.91,"stop":2580.665,"duration":13.76},{"text":"Well, this evidence was equally applicable to Reginald as it was to Jonathan. After all, it was Reginald -- Reginald's actions that were at issue. My friends also point to the instruction on statutory aggravators.","start":2580.665,"stop":2594.09,"duration":13.43},{"text":"But that disregards an entire swath of evidence that the jury heard that it could consider against Reginald.","start":2594.09,"stop":2600.71,"duration":6.62},{"text":"This was evidence, anti-mitigation evidence that the jury considered, could have caused them to remove weight from the mitigation side of the scale.","start":2600.71,"stop":2609.565,"duration":8.86},{"text":"And the instructions left the jury completely free to consider this evidence in anti-mitigation. My friends also suggest that I'm here only arguing an error of State law.","start":2609.565,"stop":2620.31,"duration":10.74},{"text":"Well, no less than the Petitioners were in Zant, Stringer, and -- and Sanders. Each of those cases recognizes that a skewing of the weighing process has to be based on State law premises. That's why this Court in Zant went so far as to certify a question to the Georgia Supreme Court. Yes, it's true that to understand the effect on the weighing process, you have to look at the State law.","start":2620.31,"stop":2644.42,"duration":24.11},{"text":"But the mere admission of evidence isn't what causes the violation here.","start":2644.42,"stop":2648.5,"duration":4.08},{"text":"It's the admission of the evidence, followed by the fact the jury was required to consider it.","start":2648.5,"stop":2653.61,"duration":5.11},{"text":"And it was required to consider it because it was part and parcel of Jonathan's mitigating evidence. And this Court has said time and again that a defendant has a constitutional right for the jury, not only to consider but to listen to a defendant's mitigating evidence.","start":2653.61,"stop":2667.62,"duration":14.01},{"text":"So by considering this evidence for Jonathan, the jury necessarily considered it against Reginald.","start":2667.62,"stop":2674.15,"duration":6.53},{"text":"After all, if you're told that Reginald had a corrupting influence on Jonathan, you can't separate that as something for Jonathan and something for Reginald.","start":2674.15,"stop":2683.59,"duration":9.44},{"text":"It's equally applicable to both. My friend also suggested that we -- we rejected a two-jury solution before trial.","start":2683.59,"stop":2694.365,"duration":10.77},{"text":"Well, we rejected that, not because of it wouldn't work to solve any prejudice in the penalty phase, but because it wouldn't work to solve any prejudice in the guilt phase. And remember, the Kansas Supreme Court found that it was actually error to keep the guilt phase joined, so we were perfectly appropriate in objecting to a two-jury solution at that phase of the trial.","start":2694.365,"stop":2714.93,"duration":20.57}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you explain that again? I thought you -- you sought only a severance at the sentencing phase.","start":2714.93,"stop":2722.71,"duration":7.78}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2722.71,"stop":2723.11,"duration":0.4},{"text":"That's not -- that's not --","start":2723.11,"stop":2724.02,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"You sought severance totally?","start":2724.02,"stop":2726.885,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Frederick Liu","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":2726.885,"stop":2727.6,"duration":0.71},{"text":"Prior to trial, on pages 25 and 26 of the Joint Appendix, we moved for severance of the entire thing. And if you look at those pages, you'll see Jonathan's attorney, Jonathan's own attorney, saying that if the penalty phase is joined, he is going to have to present evidence that, quote, \"there's no way the State would be able to introduce if Reginald was sitting here alone.\" Well, his attorney was exactly right. That's exactly what happened many months later. I see that my time is up.","start":2727.6,"stop":2761.37,"duration":33.77}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel. Mr. Green.","start":2761.37,"stop":2769.605,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: I'd like to first try and change the narrative here with some illustrations about the difference between the mitigation cases of both defendants.","start":2769.605,"stop":2781.055,"duration":11.45},{"text":"That's easily seen in the testimony of the experts. Reginald Carr presented evidence from a neuroscientist by the name of Dr. Woltersdorf that said his client had been diagnosed a -- an incurable sociopath. Jonathan Carr's forensic psychologist, clinical and forensic psychologist, got up and testified that -- that Jonathan was sensitive, he was affectionate, he had attempted suicide, and what he really was, contrary to what Mr. McAllister represented to you, was -- was depressed and schizophrenic. That is -- that is a unique illustration of exactly how different these two defendants were in their presentation, and why, again, a sequential penalty phase, even if they had been separate, wouldn't work. Reginald says he didn't want to hear or he thought it would be prejudicial if the jury heard evidence from the -- from the -- from Jonathan's witnesses about Reginald being a -- a corrupting influence.","start":2781.055,"stop":2849.075,"duration":68.02},{"text":"On the other side, Jonathan doesn't want the jury to hear from Reginald's expert. And to answer your question, Justice Kagan, that's the evidence that would not have been introduced. Justice Woltersdoft's -- or excuse me -- Dr. Woltersdoft's testimony about incurable sociopathy would not have been relevant or --","start":2849.075,"stop":2866.85,"duration":17.78}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe I'm missing something, but if -- if your client's strategy was to make Reginald as bad -- the bad actor in the case, why didn't that evidence actually go hand in hand with your client's strategy, which was to say it's all on Reginald?","start":2866.85,"stop":2883.475,"duration":16.63}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"One -- one would think that it would in -- in a typical case, and it may be that some jurors had inferred that way. The problem was that -- that the fact that the two brothers were sitting together allowed the prosecutors to repeatedly paint them with the same brush. And -- and if we take a look, for example, at JA 402, the prosecutor says to the jury in her opening argument at the beginning of the penalty -- or at the conclusion of the penalty phase, ladies and gentlemen, they have the same eye color.","start":2883.475,"stop":2918.715,"duration":35.24},{"text":"They are now wearing glasses, although their mother said Reginald doesn't need them, they share some DNA.","start":2918.715,"stop":2923.875,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So this -- maybe you can, in your experience, cure what's bothering me about the case.","start":2923.875,"stop":2929.85,"duration":5.97},{"text":"It's nothing to do with the facts, or for this -- this concern.","start":2929.85,"stop":2933.715,"duration":3.87},{"text":"It has to do with -- with Zafiro.","start":2933.715,"stop":2936.775,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2936.775,"stop":2937.51,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's the ordinary case of joint trials, right? And what the Court says is you can have the joinder as long as there isn't a serious risk that the joint trial would compromise -- it doesn't say harmless error, it says compromise -- a specific trial right, or prevent the jury from making a reliable judgment.","start":2937.51,"stop":2959.485,"duration":21.97},{"text":"That doesn't talk about harmless error. Now, that's the standard that's used in dozens and dozens and dozens of cases. Or if, in this case, we start talking about harmless error, and that you can't have the joint proceeding if there is error that is not harmless. Well, what have we done to that sentence? And what have we done to the trials that are joint in hundreds of cases that don't involve murder or death? That is the legal problem that is worrying me.","start":2959.485,"stop":2991,"duration":31.51},{"text":"And you will either cure that worry or say I've made some elementary mistake.","start":2991,"stop":2995.2,"duration":4.2},{"text":"It has nothing to do with your case.","start":2995.2,"stop":2997.17,"duration":1.97},{"text":"Say what you want, but I want to hear what you think about it.","start":2997.17,"stop":2999.97,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I don't think you've made any mistake at all, Justice Breyer.","start":2999.97,"stop":3002.23,"duration":2.26},{"text":"Indeed, I think that -- that the State of Kansas and the Solicitor General are offering nothing more than -- than the Zafiro test and using slightly different language. On page 15 of our --","start":3002.23,"stop":3012.52,"duration":10.29}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So we should not use the words \"harmless error.\" We should quote from Zafiro and say could they make a reliable judgment? Now, that sounds harder on you, because if all you have to show is the error was harmful, it sounds like an easier task you have than to show that the juror -- jury wasn't reliable.","start":3012.52,"stop":3031.76,"duration":19.24},{"text":"Or are they the same thing in your opinion?","start":3031.76,"stop":3033.61,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me -- I think they're the same thing and I think that's a generalization, but we've -- we've offered a test that actually specifies it a little bit more, Justice Breyer. In terms of saying that -- that the test should be whether there is a reasonable risk -- and I will explain the difference between reasonable and serious in a minute -- but whether there was a reasonable risk that there would be evidence introduced, material, prejudicial evidence introduced that would -- that would, in fact, not have been introduced in a severed penalty-phase proceeding. And to go back to Justice Kagan's question about the intuitive difference between these two things, they're between -- excuse me -- trials and -- and penalty-phase proceedings, the answer is that's because in a -- in a trial, the -- the relative culpability of the defendants makes a big difference with respect to who's a conspirator, who's not a conspirator, who's a principal, who's an aider and abettor. But when we turn to the penalty phase, the inquiry changes, as Mr. Liu indicated -- it changes from exactly what happened to who this person is and whether or not the jury wants to put this person to death.","start":3033.61,"stop":3100.96,"duration":67.35}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Who -- who -- if you have separate proceedings, who -- who gets to go second? Because obviously that person will have a significant advantage since they'll see all of the evidence presented in the -- in the other proceeding.","start":3100.96,"stop":3112.425,"duration":11.47}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in --","start":3112.425,"stop":3112.88,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And most of the evidence here was overlapping, so that at least you'll have -- you'll be able to see what the State thought about that evidence.","start":3112.88,"stop":3120.395,"duration":7.51},{"text":"You have sort of a dry run if you're the second person.","start":3120.395,"stop":3122.78,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in this case, respectfully, no, Mr. Chief Justice, because what the -- what the State basically said was we're relying on our evidence from the -- from the trial phase -- or from the guilt phase of this capital trial. That's exactly what the prosecutor told the jurors when they turned in to the penalty phase, and all that the prosecution did in the penalty phase was cross-examine the defense witnesses.","start":3122.78,"stop":3144.615,"duration":21.83}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but that cross-examination is important. Were there any common defense witnesses?","start":3144.615,"stop":3149.73,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"There were family members. So -- so it is true --","start":3149.73,"stop":3151.82,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So at least it would be -- it would be helpful for the second -- the person who goes second to know, well, what did the prosecutor talk -- how did the prosecutor attempt to cross-examine that witness, because I am going to call the same witness, and her testimony is going to be a lot better the second time around because you will know exactly what the cross-examination questions are going to be.","start":3151.82,"stop":3170.97,"duration":19.15}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"That might happen.","start":3170.97,"stop":3171.86,"duration":0.89},{"text":"I -- it -- it could well be that that would be -- I would consider that a -- a minor advantage, Your Honor.","start":3171.86,"stop":3177.235,"duration":5.38},{"text":"But that could be handled by the judge in -- with protective orders, with orders about -- rules against witnesses and -- and folks in the courtroom who will have another proceeding. But I would submit -- and then with respect to witnesses who might have been traumatized by these events, that -- the -- you know, a trial court could easily have a simultaneous penalty proceedings so that that witness would only have to testify once.","start":3177.235,"stop":3201.59,"duration":24.36},{"text":"The defense team on one side wouldn't get an advantage over the other.","start":3201.59,"stop":3204.69,"duration":3.1},{"text":"There would be two juries in two different courtrooms, same week, same days, the -- the witness can go back and forth between courtrooms, and there is none of the advantage --","start":3204.69,"stop":3214.07,"duration":9.38}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You would have -- the State would have to put on, basically, its guilt phase case again at the penalty phase, right?","start":3214.07,"stop":3220.78,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it would have to do that, but I would imagine that -- that with respect to cases like this, the defense attorneys are going to move right into what counts as stipulations; we will read testimony --","start":3220.78,"stop":3230.96,"duration":10.18}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I am sure you'd like to stipulate to all the facts that were proven at the guilt phase, but I doubt that the State is going to want to stipulate to those.","start":3230.96,"stop":3238.685,"duration":7.72}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"And the State might do that. And again, I think a trial judge could easily handle that by expediting matters.","start":3238.685,"stop":3244.16,"duration":5.47},{"text":"And this is what happens in a lot of the Federal trials.","start":3244.16,"stop":3246.65,"duration":2.49},{"text":"I would refer the Court to the -- to the brief of the Promise of Justice Initiative which shows that when we have joint trials, we get joint results.","start":3246.65,"stop":3252.945,"duration":6.3},{"text":"When we have severed trials, we get severed results.","start":3252.945,"stop":3255.57,"duration":2.63},{"text":"25 for 25, joint trials, same result for the defendants. Woodson says we must have individualized sentencing at the penalty phase, so I do not see why the Zafiro test would not -- would -- would work for penalty phase proceedings without some sort of change.","start":3255.57,"stop":3276.855,"duration":21.28},{"text":"There has to be some recognition that -- that penalty phase proceedings are different than -- than all the other armed robbery, drug cases.","start":3276.855,"stop":3286.44,"duration":9.59}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So how is that different from what the government said?","start":3286.44,"stop":3289.87,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- so I think we ought to lower the risk standard.","start":3289.87,"stop":3292.075,"duration":2.2},{"text":"We ought to lower the risk standard to a reasonable risk standard, not -- and that's what we propose in our brief at page 15.","start":3292.075,"stop":3297.795,"duration":5.72},{"text":"We should lower the standard because that would recognize the acute need for reliability and accuracy when it comes to penalty phase proceedings and the decision whether somebody is going to live or die.","start":3297.795,"stop":3308.56,"duration":10.76}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"You said you were going to make a distinction between serious and reasonable earlier.","start":3308.56,"stop":3316.32,"duration":7.76}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":3316.32,"stop":3316.84,"duration":0.52},{"text":"So a serious risk may be treated as a -- as a preponderance or a -- or above. With respect to reasonable, we're at a -- we're at a -- a -- maybe a likelihood.","start":3316.84,"stop":3327.055,"duration":10.21},{"text":"Maybe that's -- maybe that's perceived as 30 percent versus 55 percent or 60 percent, something like that. And indeed, this Court said in Boyde, with respect to reasonable likelihood, that is not a preponderance standard. If the Court has no further questions, we would urge --","start":3327.055,"stop":3346.585,"duration":19.53}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel. Mr. McAllister, five minutes.","start":3346.585,"stop":3352.29,"duration":5.7}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: I will try to be brief.","start":3352.29,"stop":3355.445,"duration":3.16},{"text":"The only Eighth Amendment implication that this Court has recognized that really applies to this case is I go back to the Romano case where the Court said the admission of evidence that might or might not be in violation of State law is not an Eighth Amendment concern.","start":3355.445,"stop":3372.485,"duration":17.04},{"text":"The only time the Eighth -- Eighth Amendment comes into play is when the evidence is -- involves constitutionally protected conduct. An example would be Dawson v.","start":3372.485,"stop":3381.665,"duration":9.18},{"text":"Delaware, where they sought a capital sentence.","start":3381.665,"stop":3384.56,"duration":2.89},{"text":"He was a member of the Aryan Brotherhood in prison.","start":3384.56,"stop":3386.79,"duration":2.23},{"text":"It had nothing to do with an aggregating factor.","start":3386.79,"stop":3388.79,"duration":2},{"text":"That was First Amendment-protected activity.","start":3388.79,"stop":3390.75,"duration":1.96},{"text":"The Court said that kind of thing could be an Eighth Amendment problem if you used against the defendant. Their cases -- I could be wrong, but I think all of their cases, Zant, Stringer, the others that they refer to skewing the weighing process, are not about admission of evidence, they are about invalid aggravating factors.","start":3390.75,"stop":3408.285,"duration":17.53},{"text":"So you've basically told the jury there is something else, literally, on the scale, an aggravating factor that later the State says, no, that was -- that was not correct, that should not have been there.","start":3408.285,"stop":3417.55,"duration":9.27},{"text":"That's distinguishable from this case. I -- I agree completely with Justice Scalia's point, add the dissenting justice made it in the Kansas Supreme Court: If the evidence -- the corrupting influence evidence was so prejudicial to Reginald, why did Jonathan also get a death sentence? And I would close by saying that we all agree, I think, that the Constitution values accuracy and fairness.","start":3417.55,"stop":3442.685,"duration":25.13},{"text":"But it also values finality.","start":3442.685,"stop":3444.985,"duration":2.3},{"text":"And each of these individuals received an individualized sentence, presented all the evidence they wanted to.","start":3444.985,"stop":3452.09,"duration":7.11},{"text":"The jury was instructed to consider them individually.","start":3452.09,"stop":3454.99,"duration":2.9},{"text":"And if we were to undo this now, it would be very difficult for Kansas to go back.","start":3454.99,"stop":3460.49,"duration":5.5},{"text":"We'd be talking about having to redo all of the guilt phase evidence.","start":3460.49,"stop":3463.93,"duration":3.44},{"text":"And, again, you get into questions, separate proceedings, traumatizing victims yet again.","start":3463.93,"stop":3468.81,"duration":4.88},{"text":"None of that is necessary, because at the end of the day they got a fundamentally fair proceeding that gave each of them the sentence they deserved and the jury found warranted, both under the facts of this case and the law of Kansas. We would ask that you reverse the Kansas Supreme Court on this point.","start":3468.81,"stop":3487.7,"duration":18.89}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. McAllister, I am sorry, but even if we do this and say that the sentencings didn't need to be severed, didn't the Kansas court hold on another ground that they were entitled to a new trial?","start":3487.7,"stop":3503.33,"duration":15.63}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen R. McAllister","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3503.33,"stop":3504,"duration":0.67},{"text":"So that's the third question presented in the Petition, which my understanding is that is something the Court could reconsider.","start":3504,"stop":3511.3,"duration":7.3},{"text":"It's not denied.","start":3511.3,"stop":3512.485,"duration":1.18},{"text":"The Court granted Questions 1 and 3. The other question that we presented was the only other ground that the Kansas Supreme Court gave for reversal, that's a Confrontation Clause violation in terms of some of the hearsay evidence presented in the sentencing proceedings. So if the Court were to reverse on these, deny on that question, then the Kansas Supreme Court could, in fact, rely on that ground.","start":3512.485,"stop":3534.1,"duration":21.61},{"text":"But our hope would be that the Court would do something different than that if you reverse on these two questions. Unless there are further questions, thank you.","start":3534.1,"stop":3542.68,"duration":8.58}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel. The cases are submitted.","start":3542.68,"stop":0,"duration":-3542.68}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument (No. 14-452) - October 07, 2015","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/23998","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear argument first this morning in Case 14-452, Kansas v. Gleason and the consolidated cases. General Schmidt.","start":0,"stop":10.3,"duration":10.3}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: These sentences do not offend the Eighth Amendment.","start":10.3,"stop":16.635,"duration":6.34},{"text":"Each of these jurors was able to give meaningful effect to anything and everything they heard and presented in mitigation.","start":16.635,"stop":24.59,"duration":7.95},{"text":"The verdicts reflect the reasoned moral response of these jurors to the aggravated brutality of these crimes, the weak claims for mitigation, and the individual assessment of each Respondent's moral culpability.","start":24.59,"stop":38.44,"duration":13.85}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you agree -- do you agree, whatever the Eighth Amendment does not require, that it would be better practice for the trial judge to tell the jury what the burden is on mitigators, just to ward off any possibility of confusion?","start":38.44,"stop":58.485,"duration":20.05}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"And, in fact, Justice Ginsburg, that now happens in Kansas.","start":58.485,"stop":61.63,"duration":3.15},{"text":"Subsequent to this case, the State made a decision to alter its pattern instructions, but that's not required by the Eighth Amendment.","start":61.63,"stop":67.84,"duration":6.21},{"text":"In fact, the Kansas --","start":67.84,"stop":69.07,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So why can't we presume it's required by the State law, not the Constitution? I mean, as I'm reading the decision below, the court is saying that the principles of the Eighth Amendment give voice to or support for the use of this burden and Kansas is commanding it.","start":69.07,"stop":94.015,"duration":24.95}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think not, Your Honor. This decision -- these decisions were plainly based on the Kansas Supreme Court's interpretation not of State law, but of the Eighth Amendment.","start":94.015,"stop":104.44,"duration":10.42},{"text":"And I -- I would point out a couple of reasons I believe that conclusion is inescapable. First, the court's conclusion, which is indicated at page 103 in our application, the summary of what it did, the court indicated very plainly that it was talking about mitigating evidence as required by the Eighth Amendment with no reference to State law or State practice whatsoever. Second, this argument has been presented previously when Kansas has been before this Court.","start":104.44,"stop":135.06,"duration":30.62},{"text":"This Court rejected a similar argument in Kansas v. Marsh; it rejected a similar argument in Kansas v. Cheever two terms ago.","start":135.06,"stop":142.415,"duration":7.35},{"text":"It presumably rejected or at least not embraced the similar argument made at the cert stage in these cases. And in fact, in the Kansas v. Marsh case --","start":142.415,"stop":151.05,"duration":8.64}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the Kansas Supreme Court read these cases?","start":151.05,"stop":154.585,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Perhaps I ought not answer that, Justice Scalia, but --","start":154.585,"stop":157.92,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"How can you explain it if -- if indeed our prior cases are so clear on the point?","start":157.92,"stop":162.605,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Scalia, I, of course, don't --","start":162.605,"stop":164.03,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"They don't like the death penalty.","start":164.03,"stop":165.31,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"-- know how to answer that question.","start":165.31,"stop":166.48,"duration":1.17},{"text":"I can only say that this decision -- these decisions clearly are based on that court's interpretation of the Eighth Amendment.","start":166.48,"stop":173.96,"duration":7.48}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But that can't be. Already we know and the Kansas court knew the dissent pointed out that a burden for mitigating circumstances of a preponderance of the evidence is okay, so they can't believe that no burden is required by the Constitution.","start":173.96,"stop":196.945,"duration":22.98},{"text":"They know that there is no requirement because the cases mentioned by you and Justice Scalia say that.","start":196.945,"stop":204.76,"duration":7.81},{"text":"So it has to be their view of State law.","start":204.76,"stop":208.55,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, I believe it's error, and that's why we're in front of this Court.","start":208.55,"stop":212.62,"duration":4.07},{"text":"And if there's any question about that --","start":212.62,"stop":214.19,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I suppose the issue is not what they believe, but what they said.","start":214.19,"stop":216.9,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"They did in fact --","start":216.9,"stop":217.86,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, we -- we -- we don't psychoanalyze the lower courts; we -- we look at what they said.","start":217.86,"stop":223.775,"duration":5.91},{"text":"And if they said that it's the Eighth Amendment, it's the Eighth Amendment.","start":223.775,"stop":227.97,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"In the 10 pages of the majority opinion on this subject in the Gleason case, Your Honor, there are 8 references to the Eighth Amendment; in the dissent slightly fewer pages in total, but 18 references to the Eighth Amendment.","start":227.97,"stop":239.75,"duration":11.78},{"text":"And in the Gleason decision, it's in our reply at page 8, the Kansas Supreme Court rejected the notion that the subject matter at issue here wasn't required by the Eighth Amendment, instead, wrote both recommended statements from the prior case, the one at issue.","start":239.75,"stop":254.25,"duration":14.5}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"If you prevail here on your position, is it necessary for us to remand to the Kansas Supreme Court to determine -- for them to determine whether State law would require a different result on this issue? I know there are some other issues in the case, but on this issue or --","start":254.25,"stop":276.08,"duration":21.83}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Not on this issue, Your Honor.","start":276.08,"stop":277.38,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"-- or are we permitted simply to reverse outright?","start":277.38,"stop":280.935,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe you're permitted to reverse outright.","start":280.935,"stop":283.12,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly remand on some on other issues, I understand.","start":283.12,"stop":285.435,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":285.435,"stop":285.81,"duration":0.38},{"text":"We presume there would be further proceedings below on other issues that weren't decided in the case.","start":285.81,"stop":289.61,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Why couldn't -- why couldn't the Kansas Supreme Court say on remand, thank you for enlightening us about the Eighth Amendment, but we still think that Kansas law, independent of any Federal constitutional requirement, requires juries to be told what the burden is? They could do that on remand.","start":289.61,"stop":310.785,"duration":21.18}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Ginsburg, that would, of course, be an issue that we would argue on remand if it were briefed.","start":310.785,"stop":314.7,"duration":3.91},{"text":"That's not what they did here.","start":314.7,"stop":315.94,"duration":1.24},{"text":"And, in fact, if this Court does not correct the Eighth Amendment error, I would respectfully submit we'll never get to that question on remand because the Eighth Amendment, that court's interpretation of it, will dispose of this case.","start":315.94,"stop":325.98,"duration":10.04}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"What about the other? Didn't they say something about inadmissible hearsay having prejudice -- cause prejudice in the Carr case?","start":325.98,"stop":336.27,"duration":10.29}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"In the Carr case, there was an issue with respect to that, Justice Ginsburg.","start":336.27,"stop":339.85,"duration":3.58},{"text":"It is not part of the questions that were presented or being argued in front of this Court.","start":339.85,"stop":343.99,"duration":4.14},{"text":"It was, as you know, a voluminous record with many, many issues discussed. The Kansas Supreme Court's decision below should be reversed by this Court because it made two errors.","start":343.99,"stop":354.895,"duration":10.9},{"text":"First, the Kansas Supreme Court incorrectly found in the Eighth Amendment what the dissent called a per se requirement.","start":354.895,"stop":362.085,"duration":7.19},{"text":"They found that there was a requirement in the Eighth Amendment for an affirmative instruction that mitigation need not be proven beyond a reasonable doubt.","start":362.085,"stop":369.18,"duration":7.1}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there -- to go back to the question that Justice Ginsburg has asked, as we say, this Court has never held that there is an absolute requirement that you give the reasonable doubt -- don't say it's no reasonable doubt in a mitigating case, just what you said.","start":369.18,"stop":387.36,"duration":18.18}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":387.36,"stop":387.86,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"We send it back because, as you said, they just -- if the law in the State is different, they've changed it.","start":387.86,"stop":394.655,"duration":6.79},{"text":"When they changed it, did they apply the change retroactively?","start":394.655,"stop":398.23,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor. And, in fact, if this Court --","start":398.23,"stop":400.35,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"What did they say?","start":400.35,"stop":401.84,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"The pattern instructions in Kansas that would be applicable in a circumstance like this on this subject have been changed prospectively. And we now use them.","start":401.84,"stop":408.37,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But that court's held it's only prospective?","start":408.37,"stop":410.35,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe that's been --","start":410.35,"stop":412.03,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- how can you retroactively give an instruction? Right?","start":412.03,"stop":416.61,"duration":4.58}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you very simply say, yes, have a new trial, that's how.","start":416.61,"stop":420.345,"duration":3.74},{"text":"I mean, you simply set a new sentencing hearing --","start":420.345,"stop":423.38,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"But, Your Honor, of course, there would be no need for a new trial if this Court will correct the Eighth Amendment error, which is what we're trying for --","start":423.38,"stop":428.44,"duration":5.06}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"There would be a need if Kansas law, as is now revealed by their pattern instructions, suggests that you do have to give the instruction that's -- that the -- that the defendant wants, and you'd have to have a new sentencing proceeding, wouldn't you?","start":428.44,"stop":442.035,"duration":13.6}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, not --","start":442.035,"stop":442.98,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Why not?","start":442.98,"stop":443.365,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Not unless that instruction were to apply retroactively in the case --","start":443.365,"stop":447.13,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes --","start":447.13,"stop":447.22,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and that question, of course, is not presented. In fact, there are currently 9 persons under sentence of death in Kansas and this issue, this Eighth Amendment issue, as our court has expressed it, is present in 6 of them.","start":447.22,"stop":457.105,"duration":9.88},{"text":"So two-thirds of the death penalty cases in our State are negatively affected in the event this Court were to decline to correct the Eighth Amendment error and allow the Kansas court to continue to misapply the Eighth Amendment in the manner that it's done.","start":457.105,"stop":470.32,"duration":13.21}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"How -- how was the change to the pattern instructions made? Who made it?","start":470.32,"stop":474.51,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"There's a pattern instruction committee, Your Honor, that develops these pattern instructions.","start":474.51,"stop":479.915,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it approved by the Supreme Court or is it divorced from the Supreme Court?","start":479.915,"stop":485.435,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that's correct, but I -- I don't want to swear to that, Your Honor.","start":485.435,"stop":489.2,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"You believe it's correct, that it is approved by the Court.","start":489.2,"stop":491.71,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"I want to double-check on that point, Your Honor.","start":491.71,"stop":493.535,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":493.535,"stop":493.71,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":493.71,"stop":493.97,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"My thinking is the following, so you'll understand why I ask this question. It, I think, could be the case that you're right, that this Court has never held that the Eighth Amendment requires giving such an instruction. Next question: Should it now hold it? Well, the answer to that question could be this is not a good case to decide that.","start":493.97,"stop":519.559,"duration":25.59},{"text":"Because it may be that the Kansas court has held it as to the future and may apply the future rule as to the 9 people who are involved in the past.","start":519.559,"stop":531.805,"duration":12.25},{"text":"Therefore, send it back. What do you think of that reasoning?","start":531.805,"stop":536.745,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":536.745,"stop":537.26,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Probably not much, but I'd like to know your reasons. (Laughter.)","start":537.26,"stop":540.945,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Respectfully, I -- I share your conclusion on that point, Justice Breyer.","start":540.945,"stop":544.885,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't it true, General Schmidt, that it makes a big difference whether this is done under the Federal Constitution or under Kansas law? And presumably, the Kansas Supreme Court understood that it had the capability of basing its decision on Kansas law.","start":544.885,"stop":562.22,"duration":17.34},{"text":"But if -- if it did that, it would have to take responsibility for the decisions in these cases, which involve some of the most horrendous murders that I have seen in my 10 years here.","start":562.22,"stop":576.05,"duration":13.83},{"text":"And we see practically every death penalty case that comes up anywhere in the country.","start":576.05,"stop":580.54,"duration":4.49},{"text":"These have to rank as among the worst.","start":580.54,"stop":583.975,"duration":3.44},{"text":"So it didn't take responsibility for that.","start":583.975,"stop":586.52,"duration":2.54},{"text":"It said it's the Eighth Amendment, and we have to apply the Federal Constitution. Now, it may be they will say, well, we're going to say that Kansas law requires this, but then it's their responsibility; isn't that true?","start":586.52,"stop":599.94,"duration":13.42}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Alito, I, of course, won't speculate on what the Kansas court was -- might do. I --","start":599.94,"stop":604.1,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I wasn't speculating on why they did what they did, but the consequences of basing it on the Federal Constitution.","start":604.1,"stop":610.57,"duration":6.47},{"text":"One of the consequences of basing it on the Federal Constitution is that they don't have to take responsibility for it.","start":610.57,"stop":617.39,"duration":6.82}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"I have no ability to dispute that --","start":617.39,"stop":619.24,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Do -- do you have retention elections in Kansas?","start":619.24,"stop":623.375,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"We do, Your Honor.","start":623.375,"stop":624.84,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":624.84,"stop":625.61,"duration":0.77},{"text":"And the fact -- how -- how many people are there on death row in Kansas?","start":625.61,"stop":630.27,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"There are currently 9 under sentence, with a tenth --","start":630.27,"stop":632.27,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Which would suggest that -- that Kansans, unlike our Justice Breyer, do not think the death penalty is unconstitutional and indeed very much favor it, which might suggest that a retention election that goes before such people would not come out favorably for those justices who create Kansas law that -- that would reverse these convictions. I'm just speculating, of course.","start":632.27,"stop":659.3,"duration":27.03}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Scalia, all I can say is that in these cases, it's certainly apparent to us, and I think to any fair reading, that the Kansas court relied on the Federal Eighth Amendment in making these decisions, and absent correction of those occurred by this Court will continue to do so.","start":659.3,"stop":672.97,"duration":13.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"What is this Court supposed to do when it's told its own lower courts three times before this case, or two, you must give this instruction? What -- what -- what's the Court supposed to do?","start":672.97,"stop":691.11,"duration":18.14}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you asking about what the Kansas Supreme Court is supposed to do in that case, Your Honor?","start":691.11,"stop":694.97,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":694.97,"stop":695.1,"duration":0.13},{"text":"Whether the Constitution requires it or not, it has said the better practice is to give this instruction. What's a court supposed to do? Say, willy-nilly, my lower courts can disagree with me and not do it?","start":695.1,"stop":714.57,"duration":19.47}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Sotomayor, no.","start":714.57,"stop":716.97,"duration":2.4},{"text":"And I would leave it to the Kansas court under Kansas law and practice.","start":716.97,"stop":720.78,"duration":3.81},{"text":"It is, of course, the supreme court of the State to determine what the appropriate step would be under State law.","start":720.78,"stop":725.435,"duration":4.65},{"text":"But what the Kansas court is not supposed to do in that circumstance is pivot to the Eighth Amendment and make a Federal decision that is incorrect under this Court's practices.","start":725.435,"stop":734.09,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":734.09,"stop":734.23,"duration":0.14},{"text":"And it can't -- and it can't, by doing so, immunize itself from -- from review in this Court.","start":734.23,"stop":738.99,"duration":4.76},{"text":"And that's Michigan v. Long, which -- which -- which I don't know if were cited in the brief, but Michigan v. Long, to Justice Alito's point, made it very clear that a -- a State court can't hide behind a -- a Federal law and -- and -- and be immune because there might be a State law to predicate. We have to see what they wrote.","start":738.99,"stop":760.78,"duration":21.79},{"text":"And this -- I assume that Kansas would pride itself on -- on being cited in other jurisdictions.","start":760.78,"stop":768.97,"duration":8.19},{"text":"And if it's wrong and it uses a Federal calculus that's incorrect, it's -- it's this Court's duty to reverse.","start":768.97,"stop":776.34,"duration":7.37}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Justice Kennedy, I certainly agree.","start":776.34,"stop":778.22,"duration":1.88},{"text":"And to that last point on other jurisdictions, we've identified, and they're in our briefs, at least 5 states that we believe are similarly situated, where they actually impose no burden, but don't require an affirmative instruction. And we believe, notwithstanding the back-and-forth in the briefs, that the Uniform Code of Military Justice looks much more like the Kansas system on this point than on what the Kansas Supreme Court says is constitutionally required.","start":778.22,"stop":800.24,"duration":22.02}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose -- I suppose that it is true that if you're a juror and you're considering whether or not to grant mercy, that's not something that's easily subject to a burden-of-proof analysis one way or the other.","start":800.24,"stop":816.12,"duration":15.88},{"text":"If a juror thinks I have sympathy for this person or I want to grant mercy, that -- that's not really the -- the kind of fact like you're -- you're 18 or you're 21 or your father did or didn't abandon you that can be proven in -- with a burden of proof of any sort.","start":816.12,"stop":835.66,"duration":19.54}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly correct, Justice Kennedy.","start":835.66,"stop":837.28,"duration":1.62},{"text":"And, of course, a mercy instruction was given in each of these cases.","start":837.28,"stop":840.34,"duration":3.06},{"text":"And in addition, separate and apart from the mercy instruction issue, this Court has in the past looked at what you've called catch-all instructions, like the Factor K instructions from California, has looked on them favorably.","start":840.34,"stop":851.62,"duration":11.28},{"text":"And in these cases there was a catch-all instruction given as well.","start":851.62,"stop":855.62,"duration":4},{"text":"It's an instruction 7 on Gleason 6 and 8 with respect to the Carr cases.","start":855.62,"stop":859.88,"duration":4.26},{"text":"So there was both a belt-and-suspenders alternate option.","start":859.88,"stop":862.65,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Sorry.","start":862.65,"stop":862.79,"duration":0.14},{"text":"What does that mean, a \"catch-all instruction\"?","start":862.79,"stop":864.66,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"It's the language in -- it's the last paragraph of Section 7.","start":864.66,"stop":868.39,"duration":3.73},{"text":"It reads this way, if I may, Justice Kagan: \"You may further consider as a mitigating circumstance any other aspect of the defendant's character, background, or record, and any other aspect of the offense which was presented\" -- not proven, presented -- \"in either the guilt or penalty phase which you find may serve as a basis for imposing a sentence less than death.\" And to Justice Kennedy's point, that's clearly not a finding subject to some burden of proof. It's an open-ended invitation to consider and weigh and give effect to anything else these jurors think appropriate in rendering a reasoned, moral judgment.","start":868.39,"stop":902.78,"duration":34.39}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Didn't the Court --","start":902.78,"stop":903.82,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm reading that from Gleason, and that's also in Carr?","start":903.82,"stop":906.215,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":906.215,"stop":906.78,"duration":0.56},{"text":"It's Instruction 6 and 8 in Carr.","start":906.78,"stop":908.885,"duration":2.11},{"text":"Similar language.","start":908.885,"stop":910.34,"duration":1.46},{"text":"It may not be exactly identical, but it's substantively identical.","start":910.34,"stop":912.47,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Didn't the Kansas Court say, yes, we have that, but the only burden of proof in any of the instructions was in aggravating circumstances and that the State bore that burden? And it pointed to the fact that aggravating and mitigating were mentioned in the same clause 5 or 6 times with no explanation of what the burden was for mitigating.","start":912.47,"stop":937.31,"duration":24.84},{"text":"The Kansas Court thought that the jurors could be confused or would be confused by what burden of proof was needed.","start":937.31,"stop":947.559,"duration":10.25}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Sotomayor, and that's the second reason we would respectfully ask this Court to reverse the Kansas Court, in addition to the bright-line per se rule. The Kansas Court reported it said it was applying this Court's instruction from Boyde v. California to test whether or not the Eighth Amendment is offended by instructions that are alleged to be ambiguous or confusing, which I think is what's happening there. The Kansas Court said it was applying Boyde, but then it went on to conduct no actual Boyde analysis other than what Your Honor points to, which is simply the State said repeatedly, in both cases, that there is a burden of proof beyond a reasonable doubt that the State must prove with respect to aggravators, and also with respect to the weighing factor. And the mere silence on the other side somehow led the Kansas Court to conclude that Boyde was violated because jurors would have inferred what was imposed on the State must also have been imposed on the Respondent.","start":947.559,"stop":999.24,"duration":51.68},{"text":"I just don't think that follows either logic or natural language.","start":999.24,"stop":1001.7,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think what they're saying is that some jurors would be confused. And certainly, there have been jury -- jury studies to indicate that jurors are often confused, generally, about burdens of proof.","start":1001.7,"stop":1013.88,"duration":12.18}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Sotomayor, I certainly agree that is what they seem to be saying, but the test this Court has adopted and replied repeatedly since Boyde is not that there is some speculative possibility in a hypothetical circumstance somebody might have been confused.","start":1013.88,"stop":1028.495,"duration":14.61},{"text":"It is there is a showing, that there is a reasonable likelihood that these jurors applied their instructions in a way that prevented them from considering constitutionally relevant mitigation evidence.","start":1028.495,"stop":1038.63,"duration":10.14},{"text":"There's no showing of it.","start":1038.63,"stop":1039.58,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"It is such common sense that there is a maxim of interpretation that invokes it. When -- when somebody says interest-free loans for people with good credit, it implies that there are not interest-free loans for people who don't have good credit.","start":1039.58,"stop":1059.945,"duration":20.37},{"text":"Inclusio unius, exclusio alterius. And if one says there are aggravating factors and mitigating factors, and you must prove the aggravating factors beyond a reasonable doubt, the normal understanding is you don't have to prove it beyond a reasonable doubt for the mitigating factors. That's such -- such common reasoning that -- that any juror who doesn't follow it is -- is certainly not the typical juror, and not the person for whom the jury instructions have to be devised.","start":1059.945,"stop":1093.02,"duration":33.08}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the jury instructions don't have to be devised necessarily for the Court.","start":1093.02,"stop":1099.56,"duration":6.54},{"text":"They should be understandable to jurors. And I doubt very much that any juror has heard of that maxim. But putting that aside, the Kansas Court, which has much more experience than we do with trial court decisions, has determined that confusion exists or can exist.","start":1099.56,"stop":1125.28,"duration":25.72},{"text":"Why isn't that enough for us?","start":1125.28,"stop":1128.175,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I would point you back again to the concluding paragraph, because I think it illustrates my response that -- there's suggestion of the response throughout the record, but it illustrates it well. Again, back on page 103 of the Gleason appendix, this is what our court said: \"The district court's instruction on mitigating circumstances failed to affirmatively inform the jury that mitigating circumstances need not be proven beyond a reasonable doubt.\" So there was silence on that point. Next sentence: \"And the penalty phrase\" -- \"phase instructions as a whole exacerbated the error because they referred only to the State's burden of beyond a reasonable doubt,\" which, of course, will always be true because it's constitutionally required that the jurors be informed the State, the government bears that burden beyond a reasonable doubt. The Kansas Court then concluded in the next sentence -- I won't read it because I've cited it before -- but under these circumstances, in other words, when there is an instruction that the State must prove beyond a reasonable doubt and there is silence on the other side, we conclude there is a reasonable likelihood that -- the Boyde is violated -- I'm summarizing, of course -- it is conclusory and nothing else. In other words, it is back to that per se application that was novel in the Kansas Supreme Court's holding.","start":1128.175,"stop":1193.42,"duration":65.25},{"text":"They gave it the gloss of Boyde.","start":1193.42,"stop":1195.065,"duration":1.64},{"text":"They said they were applying Boyde.","start":1195.065,"stop":1197,"duration":1.93},{"text":"But they misapplied this Court's instruction from Boyde and instead merely said here's our Boyde analysis.","start":1197,"stop":1202.8,"duration":5.8},{"text":"There's a per se violation because there is a beyond-a-reasonable-doubt instruction correctly for the State and silence on the other side. No other indication of juror misapplication or confusion. Justice Scalia, back on the point that you were raising.","start":1202.8,"stop":1220.23,"duration":17.43},{"text":"I would just say that it is -- perhaps ironic is the correct word, but frustrating from the standpoint of the government in this case -- the State in this case, that we bent over backwards to make clear to these jurors the heavy burden borne by the State. We did repeatedly tell them, at multiple places, the State bears a burden to prove aggravation beyond a reasonable doubt and to prove on the weighing factor, and that the death penalty should be imposed. The phrasing's in there; it's a normative phrase.","start":1220.23,"stop":1251.31,"duration":31.08},{"text":"It's obviously not subject directly to a burden of proof. And because we told them that repeatedly to make clear how heavy the State's burden was, that now has turned into an argument that we somehow misled the jury.","start":1251.31,"stop":1261.95,"duration":10.64}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the prosecutor in Carr did tell the jury, I'm going to create reasonable doubt as to the defendants' mitigating evidence.","start":1261.95,"stop":1270.515,"duration":8.57},{"text":"So that prosecutor didn't do what you said.","start":1270.515,"stop":1273.865,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Justice Sotomayor, the Carr records are very thick.","start":1273.865,"stop":1276.92,"duration":3.06},{"text":"And I would say on Gleason, I think it's bright line, very clear.","start":1276.92,"stop":1280.25,"duration":3.33},{"text":"We conceded the existence of all but two of those mitigating factors that were asserted in Gleason.","start":1280.25,"stop":1285.435,"duration":5.18},{"text":"And the other two merely asked was anything produced, was there any evidence on that, which this Court has said at least since Marsh is permissible.","start":1285.435,"stop":1291.47,"duration":6.04},{"text":"So I think Gleason is a clean example on behalf of the State. Carr, I'd admit, is a much longer record. It has a lot more back and forth in it.","start":1291.47,"stop":1298.08,"duration":6.61},{"text":"You had expert testimony and some back and forth on that. But even in the Carr case, this Court has instructed since Boyde, and has done so repeatedly, that in determining whether or not there's a reasonable likelihood of unconstitutional juror confusion, if the jurors thought they couldn't consider something, you look at the context of the entire trial. And if you looked at the overall instructions that were given in the Carr case, you'll also see that the Carr prosecutors -- and I'd refer the Court to pages 392 and 393 of the Joint Appendix, as well as 442 and 443 of the same -- the prosecutor told the Carr juries that the jury's task is, quote, \"to research and to analyze and to distribute the information and to weigh it and measure it and turn it upside down and look at it backwards and to have a healthy discussion about the relative merits of that which you have heard in this courtroom.\" And then went on at the secondary cite I gave you to ask the jury in the Carr cases to render a death verdict, and I quote, \"Because you have looked and listened to all the evidence, and the evidence warrants that kind of punishment.","start":1298.08,"stop":1360.685,"duration":62.61},{"text":"Anything that would reduce culpability has not been presented here.\" I offer those as examples, Justice Sotomayor, to make the point that it is, of course, always possible, particularly when dealing with the transcription of oral statements made during trial, to find a phrase here or there that, in hindsight, perhaps was inartfully crafted. But the overall thrust of these instructions, the arguments of counsel, the nature of the evidence that was put on, to Justice Kennedy's point, was these jurors were told to consider and weigh everything.","start":1360.685,"stop":1389.63,"duration":28.95},{"text":"In fact, they were literally told that phrase in Instruction 2, to consider and weigh everything admitted into evidence that would weigh on aggravation or mitigation.","start":1389.63,"stop":1397.94,"duration":8.31},{"text":"It was clear they were given an open-ended instruction, and --","start":1397.94,"stop":1401.24,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"But General, if I can understand your argument, you're saying not only that that analysis would come out the State's way, but you're saying this -- the lower court really never did that analysis at all, right? It didn't think that it was doing that analysis.","start":1401.24,"stop":1417.19,"duration":15.95},{"text":"It didn't think that that analysis was necessary because it thought that there was just a per se rule that one had to give this instruction; is that correct?","start":1417.19,"stop":1424.54,"duration":7.35}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Justice Kagan, that's not. What I'm saying is that the lower court correctly identified Boyde as the proper analysis, said that was what it was doing, but then wholly misapplied Boyde and, instead, conjured this per se rule. Their misapplication of this Court's precedent in Boyde is what resulted in their incorrect conclusion that the Eighth Amendment requires this sort of per se instruction. So it's not just that they didn't get to what they should have done and they did something different.","start":1424.54,"stop":1451.54,"duration":27},{"text":"It's that they tried to do what they should have done under this Court's precedent; they just did it wrong.","start":1451.54,"stop":1456.82,"duration":5.28},{"text":"And that's why we asked --","start":1456.82,"stop":1457.43,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I find that a little bit confusing.","start":1457.43,"stop":1458.99,"duration":1.56},{"text":"It just -- it sounds like they just sort of cited Boyde but failed to pay attention to anything Boyde said about what the analysis ought to be and instead substituted their own analysis, which was a per se rule deriving from the Eighth Amendment.","start":1458.99,"stop":1473.86,"duration":14.87}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, except, Your Honor, to your point about citing Boyde, they did more than cite Boyde.","start":1473.86,"stop":1479.06,"duration":5.2},{"text":"They also recited some of the concepts from Boyde.","start":1479.06,"stop":1482.58,"duration":3.52},{"text":"I mean, for example, the Court said -- and I believe I already mentioned this passage to you -- our court said that they looked at the context of the trial, which is something that Boyde says must be done in a proper Boyde analysis.","start":1482.58,"stop":1494.77,"duration":12.19},{"text":"But in their conclusion, the prosecutor's statements made matters worse, notwithstanding the fact it was already discussed with, Justice Sotomayor.","start":1494.77,"stop":1501.655,"duration":6.88},{"text":"I just don't believe that is a fair conclusion or an accurate conclusion.","start":1501.655,"stop":1505.12,"duration":3.46}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"What a -- what a wonderful system we've created.","start":1505.12,"stop":1508.38,"duration":3.26},{"text":"We give -- even when a State court is wrong in convicting somebody, so long as they're reasonably wrong, we uphold them.","start":1508.38,"stop":1517.72,"duration":9.34},{"text":"And when they're wrong on a legal conclusion applying our test, we jump in and reverse them, right?","start":1517.72,"stop":1527.5,"duration":9.78}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Sotomayor, all I can say is on this case, our court was wrong under the Eighth Amendment.","start":1527.5,"stop":1532.08,"duration":4.58},{"text":"We would ask for reversal. Mr. Chief Justice, with permission, I'd like to reserve the balance of my time.","start":1532.08,"stop":1536.08,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, General. Mr. Green. NOS. 14-452 AND 14-449.","start":1536.08,"stop":1548.145,"duration":12.07}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: I'd like to first address Justice Sotomayor's questions, briefly. Justice Sotomayor, you were correct, the Kansas Supreme Court has 3 times addressed this issue before, not 2 times.","start":1548.145,"stop":1564.455,"duration":16.31},{"text":"There was a case cited in the submission that we made to the Court on Monday.","start":1564.455,"stop":1568.74,"duration":4.29},{"text":"That submission was the objection to the jury instructions offered by counsel for Jonathan Carr and Reginald Carr. In that -- in that objection to the -- or excuse me -- the affirmative jury instructions offered by those attorneys.","start":1568.74,"stop":1582.32,"duration":13.58},{"text":"In those affirmative instructions, they explained that one of the reasons why they wanted an instruction that the jury should be told no beyond a reasonable doubt standard applies to mitigating circumstances is -- is a case called Harman, and that is cited at-- and, again, it's in our submission -- 254 Kansas 87 from 1993.","start":1582.32,"stop":1603.67,"duration":21.35},{"text":"Kansas --","start":1603.67,"stop":1604.11,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that true of the Gleason case? There was no -- am I right, that there was no objection to these instructions given on mitigators in Gleason? You pointed out in your letter there was in Carr.","start":1604.11,"stop":1617.505,"duration":13.4}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor. That's correct.","start":1617.505,"stop":1619.41,"duration":1.9},{"text":"But I submit for this --","start":1619.41,"stop":1621.12,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"And did you -- did you ask -- oh, it was the court in Gleason.","start":1621.12,"stop":1625.755,"duration":4.64},{"text":"Was the sentencing court asked to charge that mitigators need not be proved beyond a reasonable doubt? Was there any request to charge that was turned down?","start":1625.755,"stop":1635.98,"duration":10.22}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there was not in Gleason, Your Honor.","start":1635.98,"stop":1637.87,"duration":1.89},{"text":"But, again, these cases are consolidated for this purpose.","start":1637.87,"stop":1640.56,"duration":2.69},{"text":"And my friend on the other side of the podium here has conceded that these instructions are identical for purposes of the Eighth Amendment analysis that -- that we're going to do.","start":1640.56,"stop":1650.83,"duration":10.27},{"text":"So we do have a preserved objection, but it doesn't matter anyway.","start":1650.83,"stop":1654.75,"duration":3.92},{"text":"We would submit, Justice Ginsburg, because Kansas has a no-waiver rule for such failures to object in the Gleason case, and in any event, the Kansas Supreme Court passed on it. But I want to get back to what Kansas said about -- in the Harman case.","start":1654.75,"stop":1671.675,"duration":16.92},{"text":"It said that the jury instructions were -- and these are the same jury instructions here in a mandatory minimum case.","start":1671.675,"stop":1678.11,"duration":6.43},{"text":"Kansas has a bifurcated proceeding in mandatory minimum cases. These same jury instructions were confusing, and for precisely the reason that we have here. Then we have the Kleypas case that comes later.","start":1678.11,"stop":1689.19,"duration":11.08},{"text":"In the Kleypas case, the courts -- the Kansas Supreme Court's -- Kansas Supreme Court's analysis is exactly this: The instruction is okay on the unanimity principle for Mills and McKoy purposes.","start":1689.19,"stop":1704.47,"duration":15.28},{"text":"So it's okay. It's okay.","start":1704.47,"stop":1706.175,"duration":1.7},{"text":"But for purposes of understanding how mitigation evidence is to work, it's confusing.","start":1706.175,"stop":1714.585,"duration":8.41},{"text":"No citation to Federal authority.","start":1714.585,"stop":1716.595,"duration":2.01},{"text":"None whatsoever.","start":1716.595,"stop":1717.92,"duration":1.33},{"text":"And so they say there should be an instruction given to every penalty phase juror in Kansas -- jury in Kansas, and that is, first, let's have the non-unanimity instruction, then let's have the instruction that says no beyond a reasonable doubt.","start":1717.92,"stop":1733.66,"duration":15.74}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't understand the point you're getting to.","start":1733.66,"stop":1735.44,"duration":1.78},{"text":"What -- what is your point? That this was -- this decision was based on State law?","start":1735.44,"stop":1739.95,"duration":4.51}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, that it was based on State law. And, in fact, if you go to Scott, the next decision in the proceeding, Your Honor -- Your Honor invited us to look at the cases.","start":1739.95,"stop":1748.505,"duration":8.56},{"text":"If you go to Scott, the court says the same thing.","start":1748.505,"stop":1751.45,"duration":2.94},{"text":"We're reiterating what we said in Kleypas, and by the way, we think that implicates Federal law.","start":1751.45,"stop":1756.44,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought the whole point of our decision in Michigan v. Long was to make it clear to State courts that we weren't going to do this kind of thing.","start":1756.44,"stop":1763.08,"duration":6.64},{"text":"We weren't going to try to look, well, how many Federal cites, how many State cites.","start":1763.08,"stop":1766.46,"duration":3.38},{"text":"Unless it's clear that it's based solely on State law, then we assume it's the Federal question and Federal basis in that case.","start":1766.46,"stop":1773.65,"duration":7.19},{"text":"And -- and I assume your friend was correct about how many times the Eighth Amendment was -- was cited in the opinion.","start":1773.65,"stop":1779.62,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's probably true with respect to this decision.","start":1779.62,"stop":1782.08,"duration":2.46},{"text":"I would call the Court's attention to -- to the Gleason Pet. App. 102, in which the -- the core statement of the Kansas Supreme Court there is an interpretation of Kansas State law. With respect to your question --","start":1782.08,"stop":1796.97,"duration":14.89}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't matter under Michigan v. Long.","start":1796.97,"stop":1799.45,"duration":2.48},{"text":"It's debatable whether that's a good rule or not, but it is the rule.","start":1799.45,"stop":1803.84,"duration":4.39},{"text":"It says if there's any doubt, this Court will assume that the State court was going on the Federal ground, not the State ground.","start":1803.84,"stop":1812.64,"duration":8.8}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that, Your Honor, and I would submit that, if you look at the history of this jury instruction rule that the Kansas Supreme Court has announced, which originally -- or which ultimately was enshrined in the Kansas pattern jury instructions, that does rely solely on State law and solely on the Kansas Supreme Court's decision or interpretation of its own State law, but -- please.","start":1812.64,"stop":1836.855,"duration":24.21}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I was just going to add, are you asking us to dismiss the case because there's an adequate and independent State ground?","start":1836.855,"stop":1843.985,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"I am asking you, first, to issue an opinion that would say the origins of this rule are not Eighth Amendment.","start":1843.985,"stop":1854.185,"duration":10.2},{"text":"They're in fact Kansas State law, the Kansas Supreme Court's interpretation of its own statute.","start":1854.185,"stop":1858.325,"duration":4.14},{"text":"And second, the Court might consider dismissal of the case. But to answer your earlier question to my friend on the other side of the podium, Justice Kennedy, it would be difficult to imagine a circumstance in which this Court wouldn't say, well, you were wrong, Kansas, about the Eighth Amendment here, and therefore we're going to remand so you can resolve this issue about whether or not this is in fact a Kansas Supreme Court reading of the Kansas State law.","start":1858.325,"stop":1888.96,"duration":30.63}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But if -- if -- if this Court determines that this instruction is not confusing as a matter of Eighth Amendment law, that surely has a significance -- I would think it would have a significance on any remand proceedings that might take place.","start":1888.96,"stop":1903.365,"duration":14.4},{"text":"And plus -- and it has additional significance for the other jurisdictions that use this -- and other States that use this instruction.","start":1903.365,"stop":1911.7,"duration":8.34},{"text":"So surely we have something significant and necessary to decide under the Eighth Amendment.","start":1911.7,"stop":1916.89,"duration":5.19}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it may be that -- and that is why my first alternative suggestion was that the Court take a look at -- at this.","start":1916.89,"stop":1924.39,"duration":7.5},{"text":"And maybe this is the case that's bracketed with Michigan v. Long.","start":1924.39,"stop":1927.59,"duration":3.2},{"text":"There's a sufficient history of Kansas Supreme Court interpretation of Kansas law that would allow the Court to say this isn't a Michigan v. Long case.","start":1927.59,"stop":1937.96,"duration":10.37},{"text":"If a State supreme court simply says, look, we have a decision here.","start":1937.96,"stop":1943.5,"duration":5.54},{"text":"We think it's confusing.","start":1943.5,"stop":1944.675,"duration":1.17},{"text":"The history is it's an interpretation of State law.","start":1944.675,"stop":1946.72,"duration":2.05},{"text":"And by the way, we have support under Federal law that's -- that is not a Michigan v. Long case.","start":1946.72,"stop":1954.4,"duration":7.68}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, presumably, the Kansas Supreme Court is familiar with Michigan v. Long, as we are, and they're on notice that if they start putting the Federal authorities mentioning the Eighth Amendment 8 times, that the court is going to look at it as a decision based on Federal law. The whole point of Michigan v. Long was that -- so that we wouldn't have to do what we've been doing for the last 10 minutes, which is to debate whether a decision that mentions both State and Federal law is based on State or Federal law.","start":1954.4,"stop":1979.775,"duration":25.38}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I won't -- I won't waste more time --","start":1979.775,"stop":1981.79,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, you know, if they didn't read our Eighth Amendment cases, maybe they also didn't read Michigan v. Long.","start":1981.79,"stop":1987.59,"duration":5.8},{"text":"I mean, that's entirely understandable.","start":1987.59,"stop":1990.12,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm going to -- I'm going to demonstrate to you in a minute that they did read your Eighth Amendment cases and that they got it right, Justice Scalia.","start":1990.12,"stop":1995.825,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But would it not be true that the Kansas issue -- the Kansas law issue could be raised in a State collateral proceeding? Why is a remand necessary?","start":1995.825,"stop":2005.01,"duration":9.18}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in part because if it's a Kansas collateral proceeding, the presumption of legality and finality would attach on direct review. This case is still on direct review.","start":2005.01,"stop":2016.19,"duration":11.18},{"text":"And so I would submit, Justice Alito, that the Kansas Supreme Court ought to have the opportunity in the first instance to sort this out.","start":2016.19,"stop":2022.57,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In the ordinary case, let's say a State Supreme Court decides an issue.","start":2022.57,"stop":2026.58,"duration":4.01},{"text":"They make no -- they make no reference whatsoever to State law. They based it on the Federal Constitution.","start":2026.58,"stop":2032.11,"duration":5.53},{"text":"It comes up here; we reverse.","start":2032.11,"stop":2034.47,"duration":2.36},{"text":"We would not remand and say, well, you didn't say anything about State law, but it's possible that you might want to find that the same rule applies under State law.","start":2034.47,"stop":2043.18,"duration":8.71},{"text":"We wouldn't do it in that situation, would we? In every case like that we would remand?","start":2043.18,"stop":2048.179,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know about every case, but I can imagine that the Court would want to go back and say, well, look, Federal law doesn't work this way, but it -- but, you know, Kansas Supreme Court or State supreme court, if you think it works another way, fine.","start":2048.179,"stop":2060.435,"duration":12.26}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that what we have done in such cases? We've remanded all of those for them to say, well, you didn't mention State law, but maybe you want to think about State law?","start":2060.435,"stop":2068.435,"duration":8}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"I haven't seen a case like that. But to go to the Chief Justice's question, Michigan v. Long was -- was kind of the reverse of this case.","start":2068.435,"stop":2075.44,"duration":7.01},{"text":"It wasn't using Eighth Amendment jurisprudence to support or Federal jurisprudence just to support to add additional weight to the decision.","start":2075.44,"stop":2085.685,"duration":10.24},{"text":"It was the basis of the decision.","start":2085.685,"stop":2087.45,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2087.45,"stop":2087.66,"duration":0.21},{"text":"If we assume for the sake of argument that we would not do that in every case, then what you are proposing is that we do it here because you think there's a sufficient -- there's sufficient uncertainty about the basis for the decision. And then we're going to add that into the situation in all of these cases of deciding, is there enough? Well, they cited some State cases, they might -- we're going to have to be making these decisions in every one of these cases.","start":2087.66,"stop":2111.585,"duration":23.93}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would submit that this would be such a case, especially given the history of -- of the Kansas Supreme Court's decisions on this issue interpreting its own statue. But if I might, Your Honor --","start":2111.585,"stop":2122.88,"duration":11.3}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"The other States that have no mitigating burden, do you know how many of them require an instruction just like this one?","start":2122.88,"stop":2132.21,"duration":9.33}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2132.21,"stop":2132.64,"duration":0.43},{"text":"We cited in our brief at -- our Gleason brief at pages, I think, 27 and 28, Your Honor, that -- that there are 24 States that expressly require a statement to the jury about what the burden of proof is with respect to mitigating circumstances.","start":2132.64,"stop":2149.515,"duration":16.88},{"text":"That is out of 31 states remaining in the United States that have the death penalty, Your Honor.","start":2149.515,"stop":2155.2,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"You're not saying that that's required by the Eighth Amendment; is that right? You're not advocating a per se rule that such instructions are necessary.","start":2155.2,"stop":2163.68,"duration":8.48}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2163.68,"stop":2164.18,"duration":0.5},{"text":"That's right, Justice Kagan.","start":2164.18,"stop":2165.19,"duration":1.01},{"text":"We're not -- we're not advocating that kind of per se rule.","start":2165.19,"stop":2167.97,"duration":2.78},{"text":"In fact, one could imagine a set of circumstances -- a set of instructions that are silent with respect to mitigation, but nonetheless would pass muster under the Eighth Amendment.","start":2167.97,"stop":2177.755,"duration":9.79}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"So could I -- could I talk about the circumstances of this case?","start":2177.755,"stop":2180.745,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Please.","start":2180.745,"stop":2181.145,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is, you know, you have an instruction here that is unfortunate in its juxtaposition of the reasonable doubt standard and the reference to mitigating circumstances.","start":2181.145,"stop":2191.395,"duration":10.25},{"text":"And, you know, it is unfortunate, and I can see why they changed their pattern instructions. But -- but we've said that the analysis is a holistic one.","start":2191.395,"stop":2201.13,"duration":9.74},{"text":"We look at everything.","start":2201.13,"stop":2202.585,"duration":1.45},{"text":"You also have this mercy instruction.","start":2202.585,"stop":2205.165,"duration":2.58},{"text":"You have a catch-all instruction.","start":2205.165,"stop":2207.32,"duration":2.16},{"text":"You have, in both cases, arguments by the prosecutors that indicate fairly clearly that this is really all up to the jurors in Gleason.","start":2207.32,"stop":2217.09,"duration":9.77},{"text":"It says, \"Mitigating circumstances are every juror's individual choice.\" In -- in Carr, the prosecutor says, \"Anything in fairness may be considered as extenuating.\" So I guess the question is, even if this is a really unfortunate wording in the reasonable doubt/mitigating circumstances juxtaposition, why doesn't all of this other stuff indicate that no juror was likely to be confused?","start":2217.09,"stop":2248.105,"duration":31.01}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the unfortunate wording that Your Honor refers to is repeated throughout these instructions.","start":2248.105,"stop":2254.355,"duration":6.25},{"text":"Please let me demonstrate here.","start":2254.355,"stop":2256.385,"duration":2.03},{"text":"With -- with respect to the findings of -- findings of aggravating circumstances, every time the Court is told that it must find aggravating circumstances beyond a reasonable doubt, the same sentence says, \"And any mitigating circumstances found to exist.\" There is repeated parallelism in these -- in these instructions with respect to the use of the verbs. Let's go to Justice Scalia's point earlier with respect to what a reasonable juror would have known.","start":2256.385,"stop":2284.945,"duration":28.56},{"text":"The juror -- if you look at Instruction No. 1, Instruction No. 1 says that -- reminds the jury that the --","start":2284.945,"stop":2290.18,"duration":5.23}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Which -- which case? In which case, Gleason?","start":2290.18,"stop":2292.935,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2292.935,"stop":2293.37,"duration":0.43},{"text":"I'm sorry, Your Honor. This would be in our Gleason app, Appendix 1(a). Instruction No. 1 says that when a Defendant -- excuse me.","start":2293.37,"stop":2305.47,"duration":12.1},{"text":"\"The laws of Kansas provide that a separate sentencing proceeding shall be conducted when a Defendant has been found guilty.\" Now, the verb \"find\" or \"finding\" appears 7 times in the -- throughout the instructions saying that the jury must find mitigating circumstances.","start":2305.47,"stop":2322.335,"duration":16.87},{"text":"Three times in the instructions, at crucial points in -- in Instruction No. 10, which I'll ask us to look at in a minute, and Instruction No. 12, which is the verdict, the jury is referred to -- or the jury is asked to make findings with respect to aggravating circumstances.","start":2322.335,"stop":2338.56,"duration":16.22},{"text":"So it's the same exercise throughout.","start":2338.56,"stop":2340.9,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But the jury was also aware that there was a big difference between aggravators and mitigators.","start":2340.9,"stop":2346.97,"duration":6.07},{"text":"They were told they had to be unanimous on the -- on the aggravators.","start":2346.97,"stop":2352.475,"duration":5.51},{"text":"But on mitigators, each jury -- each juror was to make the determination for herself and, moreover, that the same mitigator need not be found by all the jurors.","start":2352.475,"stop":2365.65,"duration":13.18},{"text":"So the -- the aggravators, unanimous, they all have to agree on the aggravated.","start":2365.65,"stop":2371.965,"duration":6.32},{"text":"Mitigator, one could say this one, the other could say that one, and that would be okay.","start":2371.965,"stop":2378.28,"duration":6.32}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I might agree with that, Your Honor, except for the jury was expressly told in Instruction No. 7 that -- that with respect to mitigators, it didn't have to be unanimous.","start":2378.28,"stop":2386.75,"duration":8.47},{"text":"However, the jury -- the instructions went on.","start":2386.75,"stop":2389.85,"duration":3.1},{"text":"It continued to draw parallels with respect to the burden of proof between finding mitigators and finding aggravators.","start":2389.85,"stop":2396.88,"duration":7.03}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Don't you -- don't you think it's -- it's sort of hard to contemplate each juror -- each juror's ability to find mitigators on his or her own without regard to whether others find the same mitigator? Isn't that somewhat incompatible with -- with the juror's belief that the juror had to find it beyond a reasonable doubt? My goodness, if it's beyond a reasonable doubt, you would think every other juror would find the same mitigator, and they were expressly told that they don't have to find the same mitigator.","start":2396.88,"stop":2429.435,"duration":32.55}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Beyond a reasonable doubt is the only -- the only standard that the jury is offered, Your Honor.","start":2429.435,"stop":2434.41,"duration":4.97},{"text":"It's the only one that they know.","start":2434.41,"stop":2435.94,"duration":1.53},{"text":"It's the one that they've sat through the guilt phase with.","start":2435.94,"stop":2438.56,"duration":2.62},{"text":"It's now the one that they're trying to apply in the sentencing phase, executing a moral -- pardon the pun -- executing a moral judgment as to whether a defendant should live or die. So with respect to what jurors might say to one another in the jury room, one can imagine a situation where one juror says, mercy, I'm not -- you know, maybe there should be mercy.","start":2438.56,"stop":2459.87,"duration":21.31},{"text":"Another -- another juror says to that juror, well, I didn't -- I didn't see enough evidence for that.","start":2459.87,"stop":2464.26,"duration":4.39},{"text":"I mean, are you certain mercy should be applied here? No.","start":2464.26,"stop":2466.9,"duration":2.64},{"text":"You know, you have to be certain that mercy applies here. I don't think that's a farfetched notion at all, especially when you look at an instruction like No. 10, which is on page 5A of the Joint Appendix.","start":2466.9,"stop":2480.03,"duration":13.13},{"text":"And Instruction 10 draws an express parallel and uses the verb \"to find,\" Your Honor.","start":2480.03,"stop":2484.96,"duration":4.93},{"text":"\"If you find unanimously beyond a reasonable doubt that one or more aggravating circumstances exist and that they are not outweighed by any mitigating circumstances found to exist, then you shall impose a sentence of death.\" Let's jump down to the next paragraph.","start":2484.96,"stop":2500.65,"duration":15.69},{"text":"The next paragraph says, \"However\" --","start":2500.65,"stop":2502.15,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Where are you quoting from?","start":2502.15,"stop":2503.45,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":2503.45,"stop":2504.055,"duration":0.61},{"text":"Page 5A of the Gleason Appendix --","start":2504.055,"stop":2506.81,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, the Gleason.","start":2506.81,"stop":2507.685,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"-- red -- red brief.","start":2507.685,"stop":2508.89,"duration":1.2},{"text":"My apologies, Your Honor. The next paragraph says --","start":2508.89,"stop":2511.82,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"You put it in the red brief.","start":2511.82,"stop":2513.04,"duration":1.22},{"text":"It's also in the petition for writ of certiorari appendix, the white appendix.","start":2513.04,"stop":2518.09,"duration":5.05},{"text":"Gleason 133, page 133 of the white.","start":2518.09,"stop":2522.945,"duration":4.86}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"The second paragraph of Instruction No. 10 says, \"However, if one or more juries is not\" -- \"jurors is not persuaded beyond a reasonable doubt on the burden of proof in the paragraph above.\" So, again, the jury is called to look at the beyond the reasonable doubt standard when assessing both aggravating and mitigating circumstances in parallel. And, again, this is the only -- this is the only standard that the jury has been exposed to throughout the trial.","start":2522.945,"stop":2555.86,"duration":32.91}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Your proposal is that -- is that the floor was not telling them, mitigators don't have to be shown beyond a reasonable doubt.","start":2555.86,"stop":2563.88,"duration":8.02},{"text":"But that still doesn't tell the jury what the burden of proof is on mitigators. Why are you urging beyond -- you don't have to find beyond a reasonable doubt.","start":2563.88,"stop":2575.41,"duration":11.53},{"text":"Okay.","start":2575.41,"stop":2575.82,"duration":0.41},{"text":"So what do you have to find in order to accept a mitigator?","start":2575.82,"stop":2580.93,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't expressly say that and -- Justice Ginsburg.","start":2580.93,"stop":2584.11,"duration":3.18},{"text":"That's the whole problem, is that I -- I respectfully disagree with Justice Scalia. A lawyer might look at these instructions and say, aha, the fact that there is an absence or a silence with respect to what the burden of proof is as to mitigating instructions creates a negative implication.","start":2584.11,"stop":2598.09,"duration":13.98}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I have the same question.","start":2598.09,"stop":2599.14,"duration":1.05},{"text":"Suppose the jury is instructed you -- mitigators do not have to be proved beyond a reasonable doubt.","start":2599.14,"stop":2605.52,"duration":6.38},{"text":"And then the jury sends a question, well, what is the burden of proof on mitigators? How should the trial judge answer that?","start":2605.52,"stop":2612.565,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"In Kansas, the answer is, it's a burden of production and a burden of production only. And all that means is --","start":2612.565,"stop":2616.56,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"We're asking under the Eighth Amendment -- or at least that's my interest -- under the Eighth Amendment, what is required in response to Justice Alito's question? I didn't mean to interrupt.","start":2616.56,"stop":2626.5,"duration":9.94}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it may be just the negative, that there is no -- that there is no burden of -- there is no burden of proof, and each of you as individual jurors should consider all of the evidence. I mean, it's about weighing and -- and maybe the judge could say to the jury, you should -- you should consider and you should weigh all of the evidence that the defendant --","start":2626.5,"stop":2644.35,"duration":17.85}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Wait.","start":2644.35,"stop":2644.69,"duration":0.34},{"text":"It's not a matter -- we're asking the factual finding of whether the mitigator existed, not weighing the mitigators against the aggravators, the factual finding of whether the mitigator existed, whether indeed this defendant had a troubled childhood or whatever else.","start":2644.69,"stop":2663.1,"duration":18.41},{"text":"What is the burden that the juror has to sustain in order to come to that judgment?","start":2663.1,"stop":2671.045,"duration":7.95}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, consistent with -- with Woodson and Lockett and that -- that entire line of cases, that -- that -- the exact language is, is the jury can't be precluded from considering any relevant mitigating circumstances.","start":2671.045,"stop":2684.245,"duration":13.2}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So anything -- anything that was presented to them.","start":2684.245,"stop":2686.695,"duration":2.45},{"text":"I think you said earlier burden of production.","start":2686.695,"stop":2688.595,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Any -- any --","start":2688.595,"stop":2689.28,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's what the instruction said.","start":2689.28,"stop":2690.875,"duration":1.59},{"text":"When you're considering mitigating circumstance, you -- back on any aspect of the offense which was presented in either the guilt or penalty phase.","start":2690.875,"stop":2700.295,"duration":9.42},{"text":"If it was presented to the jury, they should consider it.","start":2700.295,"stop":2703.715,"duration":3.42},{"text":"I don't --","start":2703.715,"stop":2704.975,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but that -- that doesn't -- I mean, that doesn't speak to the burden of proof.","start":2704.975,"stop":2708.53,"duration":3.56},{"text":"It -- and it does relate to both aggravating and mitigating circumstances.","start":2708.53,"stop":2712.28,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it says they have to consider anything that was presented, not things they found beyond a reasonable doubt.","start":2712.28,"stop":2718.325,"duration":6.04},{"text":"If it was presented, they need -- they can consider it.","start":2718.325,"stop":2721.26,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"If the -- if the instruction said that alone, then the instructions might be okay. And that's precisely why we're answering Justice Kagan's question that we're not saying that the Eighth Amendment commands that juries be instructed --","start":2721.26,"stop":2731.14,"duration":9.88}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So the instruction said something that you think is okay, and consider evidence that's presented.","start":2731.14,"stop":2736.32,"duration":5.18},{"text":"But you say, well, we have to draw a negative inference from what it said about aggravating circumstances to outweigh what would have been an acceptable instruction on its own.","start":2736.32,"stop":2745.355,"duration":9.03}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I'm saying that -- that consistent drawing of parallels between the two without stating exactly what the burden of proof is with respect to mitigating circumstance creates a reasonable likelihood that there would be confusion.","start":2745.355,"stop":2758.25,"duration":12.89}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":2758.25,"stop":2759.05,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey T. Green","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2759.05,"stop":2767.984,"duration":8.93}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Katyal.","start":2767.984,"stop":2771.71,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: A man is being put to death under jury instructions that are so confusing that there is a reasonable likelihood that some juries would interpret those instructions to bar consideration of the mitigating evidence and others would not.","start":2771.71,"stop":2785.44,"duration":13.73},{"text":"That ambiguity and inequity is impermissible under the Eighth Amendment. Now, the State's answer is the instructions allowed the jury in a catch-all provision to consider everything as mitigating.","start":2785.44,"stop":2796.185,"duration":10.74},{"text":"That's irrelevant.","start":2796.185,"stop":2797.21,"duration":1.03},{"text":"There are two fundamentally different questions.","start":2797.21,"stop":2799.58,"duration":2.37},{"text":"The first is the \"what.\" What kinds of circumstances count as mitigating? And second is the \"how.\" How does a jury determine if those circumstances exist in a given case? So --","start":2799.58,"stop":2809.82,"duration":10.24}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The circumstances -- the circumstances that count as -- as mitigating, 4(a) of the -- the Gleason brief, \"any other aspect of the defendant's character, background or record, and any other aspect of the offense which was presented.\"","start":2809.82,"stop":2825.615,"duration":15.79}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":2825.615,"stop":2827.23,"duration":1.62},{"text":"We agree that, for example, the jury was instructed that Reginald Carr's child abuse, if it existed, could be a mitigating factor.","start":2827.23,"stop":2834.755,"duration":7.53},{"text":"The question is: How was a jury to determine whether Reginald Carr was abused in the first place as a child? So the catch-all provision doesn't answer that question. Now, General Schmidt's answer is, well, look at the language of instruction 2.","start":2834.755,"stop":2847.62,"duration":12.86},{"text":"And, Mr. Chief Justice, I think you were referring to that.","start":2847.62,"stop":2849.87,"duration":2.25},{"text":"This is what they say -- what he says in their reply brief at page --","start":2849.87,"stop":2853.01,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":2853.01,"stop":2853.38,"duration":0.37},{"text":"I was quoting from 7.","start":2853.38,"stop":2854.8,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2854.8,"stop":2855.345,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe it's the same as 2.","start":2855.345,"stop":2857.42,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In 7 -- in 7 -- in 7, I don't see quite the same thing.","start":2857.42,"stop":2865,"duration":7.58},{"text":"But -- but I -- I think our -- out general point here is that this Court has said repeatedly in Abdul-Kabir and in Braverman that the mere presentation of evidence is enough.","start":2865,"stop":2874.6,"duration":9.6},{"text":"The evidence has to be given full effect as a mitigating circumstance. And I understand that different people can look at this -- these set of instructions as a whole and come up with different ways of interpreting them.","start":2874.6,"stop":2886.22,"duration":11.62},{"text":"But this Court's decision in Boyde says as long as there is a reasonable likelihood that a jury could read them in a confusing way and bar the consideration of mitigating evidence, that is enough. Now, Justice Scalia, you said, well, that doesn't square with common sense.","start":2886.22,"stop":2900.09,"duration":13.87},{"text":"What about an example like, quote, \"interest-free loans for people with good credit\"? Now, our argument is not simply that the jury instruction said beyond a reasonable doubt, though they did 9 times.","start":2900.09,"stop":2911.88,"duration":11.79},{"text":"It's that they coupled the beyond a reasonable doubt with the language found to exist, that mitigating circumstances must be found to exist 9 times. And so, Justice Scalia --","start":2911.88,"stop":2921.26,"duration":9.38}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So you say something -- if you're considering whether to retire, you said you should be absolutely sure you have enough money to live on and you ought to think about whether you're going to be bored.","start":2921.26,"stop":2931.04,"duration":9.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2931.04,"stop":2931.42,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You wouldn't think you had to be absolutely sure you were going to be bored.","start":2931.42,"stop":2933.96,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me just do it, Mr. Chief Justice, with respect to the -- the hypothetical that Justice Scalia said.","start":2933.96,"stop":2938.88,"duration":4.92},{"text":"If -- if the hypo was interest-free loans should be given to those found to have good credit, found to have good credit, which mirrors these instructions, and then the language used found with a certain standard beyond a reasonable doubt, or whatever, I think it's absolutely plausible that people would read that instruction and say that applies just as much to people without good credit. They'd apply the same standard.","start":2938.88,"stop":2962.68,"duration":23.8},{"text":"And that squares not just with the experience in the States.","start":2962.68,"stop":2965.925,"duration":3.25},{"text":"At least 24 States are using this, if -- if not every State.","start":2965.925,"stop":2969.32,"duration":3.39},{"text":"They can't point to a single State that says found to exist occurs in the jury instructions 9 times.","start":2969.32,"stop":2974.84,"duration":5.52},{"text":"It's not just the absence of an affirmative instruction, it's that these instructions are injecting confusion and uncertainty. And the distinction here is that you can have two men going to -- having committed virtually the same crime with the same aggravating and mitigating circumstances; one will be sentenced to death, one to life, simply because of a legal interpretation of what the jury instructions say.","start":2974.84,"stop":2997.69,"duration":22.85},{"text":"That is not --","start":2997.69,"stop":2998.12,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If were on a -- I'm sorry. Finish the sentence.","start":2998.12,"stop":3000,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I was just going to say, that is not death for the worst offender, Mr. -- Justice Alito, that's -- that's -- that's the death penalty to be imposed for the worst interpretation of jury instructions.","start":3000,"stop":3010.34,"duration":10.34}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if I were on a jury and I were told that the burden -- that mitigators do not have to be proved beyond a reasonable doubt, I would find that confusing because then I would ask what is the -- the burden of proof on mitigators? And I don't think there's any way, really, to answer that question. So maybe this is a situation like trying to define reasonable doubt where less is more.","start":3010.34,"stop":3036.4,"duration":26.06},{"text":"It's better not to get into the question of burden of proof at all. And let me -- just to finish this -- this suggestion, and maybe it's misdirected, but you mentioned the mitigator of -- of child abuse.","start":3036.4,"stop":3051.335,"duration":14.93},{"text":"What would -- if there is any burden of proof, what would be the fact as to which it would apply? The overall category that this person had a bad childhood or that the -- the individual was beaten by his mother or beaten by his father or subjected to sexual abuse or was around people who were using drugs? Unless you define what the mitigators are, which can't be done, I don't see how you can apply any kind of burden of proof.","start":3051.335,"stop":3080.11,"duration":28.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Justice Alito, I think this Court has never said that if jury instructions are, by silence, confusing, that that silence alone is enough to rise to an Eighth Amendment violation.","start":3080.11,"stop":3090.625,"duration":10.51},{"text":"Here, our point is that the instructions themselves injected the confusion.","start":3090.625,"stop":3095.23,"duration":4.61},{"text":"And so I don't think this Court is going to police every possible thing that the jury might thought in their heads.","start":3095.23,"stop":3100.76,"duration":5.53},{"text":"The point is here they mentioned only one standard, beyond a reasonable doubt.","start":3100.76,"stop":3104.42,"duration":3.66},{"text":"They mentioned it 9 times.","start":3104.42,"stop":3105.58,"duration":1.16},{"text":"And they said that the mitigating circumstances had to be found to exist. If the jury interpreted it this way, then this Court -- then the Court would be blessing a jury instruction on beyond a reasonable doubt for the first time ever in its history that said that a jury, all 12 of them, might have believed mitigating circumstances actually existed and could not give it effect.","start":3105.58,"stop":3125.49,"duration":19.91},{"text":"That is what the effect of --","start":3125.49,"stop":3126.47,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what burden of proof do you think the jury applied with respect to the showing of mercy?","start":3126.47,"stop":3132.72,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3132.72,"stop":3133.08,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They were clearly instructed that they can show mercy.","start":3133.08,"stop":3135.36,"duration":2.28},{"text":"So what -- they didn't say anything about the burden of proof.","start":3135.36,"stop":3138.13,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And Mr. Chief Justice, they were clearly instructed that mercy was a, quote, \"a mitigating factor.\" And so they were then told 9 times that they had to find a mitigating factor.","start":3138.13,"stop":3148.03,"duration":9.9}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So you think they had -- they would have interpreted that I have to determine whether to extend mercy beyond a reasonable doubt?","start":3148.03,"stop":3154.09,"duration":6.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely, Your Honor.","start":3154.09,"stop":3154.88,"duration":0.79},{"text":"I think this Court has said many times that we presume a jury follows its instructions, and this is a perfect example of that --","start":3154.88,"stop":3160.52,"duration":5.64}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I know.","start":3160.52,"stop":3160.69,"duration":0.17},{"text":"But you're -- you're begging the question to say the instruction was this and the jury didn't follow it.","start":3160.69,"stop":3164.96,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I don't think so, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3164.96,"stop":3167.46,"duration":2.5},{"text":"I think this is a perfect example of how mercy would have been applied beyond a reasonable doubt.","start":3167.46,"stop":3171.24,"duration":3.78},{"text":"If there was case for mercy after reading all of the -- all the sentencing proceedings, it was that Reginald Carr had been abused badly as a child.","start":3171.24,"stop":3178.605,"duration":7.37},{"text":"And that's why mercy should have extended.","start":3178.605,"stop":3180.55,"duration":1.95},{"text":"We are -- we're talking about death-qualified jurors here who already can't extend mercy just simply because death is on the line.","start":3180.55,"stop":3186.68,"duration":6.13},{"text":"There had to be something additional.","start":3186.68,"stop":3188.13,"duration":1.45},{"text":"That something additional, in the context of this case, was all about the child abuse of Reginald Carr. And, Justice Kagan, that's exactly what the State, time and again, Joint Appendix pages 250 to 256, said that -- that Reginald Carr did not meet his burden of proof on.","start":3188.13,"stop":3203.57,"duration":15.44},{"text":"And so this was front and center at the mitigating phase of the trial.","start":3203.57,"stop":3207.865,"duration":4.29},{"text":"This was extremely confusing, I think, to a jury.","start":3207.865,"stop":3210.43,"duration":2.57},{"text":"And, of course, this Court's decision in Boyde has a far lower standard than that.","start":3210.43,"stop":3214.2,"duration":3.77},{"text":"It's simply just was there something more than a possibility, it doesn't even have to be 50 percent, that the jury interpreted the instructions the wrong way.","start":3214.2,"stop":3222.515,"duration":8.32}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Katyal, Kansas has already answered this question, hasn't it? Its requirement is that a jury be instructed both that mitigation need not be proven beyond a reasonable doubt, and, second, that the jury be told it has no -- that there is no burden of proof.","start":3222.515,"stop":3242,"duration":19.49}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":3242,"stop":3242.53,"duration":0.53},{"text":"And just like in Maryland v. Mills where this Court, under the Eighth Amendment, looked to that, here it's significant that not even Kansas is defending the rule that these jury instructions left the jury with the impression of.","start":3242.53,"stop":3253.775,"duration":11.24},{"text":"I mean, indeed, I'm not aware of a single State that does so.","start":3253.775,"stop":3256.28,"duration":2.51},{"text":"There's no amici on the State's side saying that this is going to impose any sort of harm to them.","start":3256.28,"stop":3261.15,"duration":4.87},{"text":"This is the most modest fix in the world.","start":3261.15,"stop":3263.405,"duration":2.26},{"text":"It could be done not just with an affirmative instruction, it could be done by just striking out the words \"found to exist\" out of the jury instructions.","start":3263.405,"stop":3270.04,"duration":6.63}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you think the jury -- if you -- are they supposed to consider things they didn't find to exist?","start":3270.04,"stop":3275.34,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no.","start":3275.34,"stop":3275.75,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it's a bit of a stretch to say found to exist implies a particular standard of proof.","start":3275.75,"stop":3280.22,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think so at all, Your Honor.","start":3280.22,"stop":3281.28,"duration":1.06},{"text":"I think found to exist, that's the most natural way of reading it.","start":3281.28,"stop":3283.67,"duration":2.39},{"text":"And if there's any doubt, just look at Instruction No. 1.","start":3283.67,"stop":3286.07,"duration":2.4},{"text":"The first thing the jury was told -- this is at Petition Appendix page 500 of the Reginald Carr petition.","start":3286.07,"stop":3291.96,"duration":5.89},{"text":"\"The laws of Kansas provide a separate sentencing proceeding shall be conducted when a defendant has been found guilty of capital murder.\" That's what they're told after hearing months of testimony about whether or not the Carrs committed the crime under what standard? The beyond-a-reasonable-doubt standard. That was the only thing the jury was told, time and again, both at the guilt phases, the 9 times in the mitigating phase of this trial.","start":3291.96,"stop":3315.71,"duration":23.75},{"text":"It thinks -- it's absolutely reasonable for a jury to have interpreted the jury instructions to say that's the standard that applies here. And boy, if that's the standard that applied in this case, that is unlike any proceeding in Anglo-American jurisprudence to my knowledge.","start":3315.71,"stop":3331.43,"duration":15.72}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What does it mean to say there's no burden of proof?","start":3331.43,"stop":3335.61,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it means that -- that --","start":3335.61,"stop":3337.7,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Every juror decides individually?","start":3337.7,"stop":3339.83,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that -- in Kansas, I think that's right.","start":3339.83,"stop":3342.56,"duration":2.73},{"text":"Now, of course you could have minimum thresholds, evidence, and relevance, and so on, as this Court's decision in Tennard said. This is the opposite.","start":3342.56,"stop":3349.41,"duration":6.85},{"text":"This is the highest standard in all of law, beyond a reasonable doubt.","start":3349.41,"stop":3353.07,"duration":3.66},{"text":"It's never been done.","start":3353.07,"stop":3354.355,"duration":1.28},{"text":"And these jury instructions did so. And look, I understand that we could read these facts and say these are horrific crimes, as you said, Justice Alito.","start":3354.355,"stop":3361.935,"duration":7.58},{"text":"But so, too, Reginald Carr had a horrific upbringing.","start":3361.935,"stop":3365.065,"duration":3.13},{"text":"And I think the jury was entitled, and this Court's decision in Stringer says, that it is -- when -- when the injection of an arbitrary factor is put in and two juries could reach different results on the same facts, that violates the Eighth Amendment.","start":3365.065,"stop":3377.995,"duration":12.93}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel. Case 14-452 is -- oh, I'm sorry.","start":3377.995,"stop":3384.34,"duration":6.35},{"text":"You have rebuttal time. (Laughter.)","start":3384.34,"stop":3387.85,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You have, in fact, four minutes of it.","start":3387.85,"stop":3389.965,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, I'm anxious on the point.","start":3389.965,"stop":3393.465,"duration":3.5},{"text":"Thank you. Two or three points as time allows, Mr. Chief Justice. First on Mr. Katyal's point that the issue here is the how and not the what.","start":3393.465,"stop":3403.185,"duration":9.72},{"text":"I would come back to the point that there was both a catch-all and a mercy instruction here.","start":3403.185,"stop":3407.66,"duration":4.47},{"text":"And I would further point this Court to what this Court has suggested in the past. This Court has fairly consistently suggested that the cure to a Lockett type of error, that there was something presented that might not have been able to be given effect, would be catch-all or mercy types of instructions. And I would refer you to pages 310 and 11 of Penry 1 where it wasn't the Court, but it was defense who requested a mercy instruction that was not granted. And as a result, the case wound up in front of this Court. But also suggest that you look at page 803 on Penry 2 where this Court suggested -- Justice O'Connor writing -- that a catch-all instruction well crafted would have been the cure for the error this Court found in Penry 2. A similar implication at page 242 in Abdul-Kabir, and a similar implication in page 308 of Blystone.","start":3407.66,"stop":3451.64,"duration":43.98},{"text":"So I think Kansas has done here precisely what the Court has repeatedly suggested --","start":3451.64,"stop":3456.84,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the -- I know it's your rebuttal.","start":3456.84,"stop":3458.35,"duration":1.51},{"text":"What's the catch-all instruction you rely on?","start":3458.35,"stop":3460.37,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"The catch-all instruction is the last paragraph of Instruction No. 7.","start":3460.37,"stop":3464.61,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Of 7.","start":3464.61,"stop":3464.96,"duration":0.35},{"text":"Of 7.","start":3464.96,"stop":3465.365,"duration":0.4},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3465.365,"stop":3465.72,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3465.72,"stop":3466.15,"duration":0.43},{"text":"Correct.","start":3466.15,"stop":3466.55,"duration":0.4},{"text":"And the mercy instruction is earlier.","start":3466.55,"stop":3467.9,"duration":1.35},{"text":"I believe it's the second paragraph in Gleason. Secondly, with respect to Justice Ginsburg's observation that there -- a juror would have noticed that there's a different between the use of finding with respect to unanimity, or finding in another context, suggesting that this argument's not very persuasive, that the mere use of the word \"find\" repeatedly somehow created confusion, I think that's correct.","start":3467.9,"stop":3489.17,"duration":21.27},{"text":"And I think there's other contrast in this record that shows it. For example, with respect to the verdict forms.","start":3489.17,"stop":3494.685,"duration":5.51},{"text":"In those cases where the beyond a reasonable doubt language is included, finding is included with respect to both aggravation and mitigation, but the jurors were asked to check the box on what aggravators they had found.","start":3494.685,"stop":3506.005,"duration":11.32},{"text":"They weren't asked to do anything like that with respect to mitigators. Now, a lay juror, being asked to do one task for one purpose and a different task for a different purpose, is not likely to conclude that the two tasks are in some way equivalent. Likewise, to the point that was suggested earlier, Mr. Katyal correctly points out that the mercy instruction is described as a mitigating circumstance. That's absolutely true, but it certainly doesn't follow that the jury would have thought that they have to apply some burden of proof to mercy.","start":3506.005,"stop":3533.2,"duration":27.19},{"text":"It's an act of grace. That's the entire point of mercy.","start":3533.2,"stop":3535.885,"duration":2.69},{"text":"And that further suggests that it wasn't reasonable to conclude that reading these words \"find\" time and again somehow led them to an equivocal -- an equivalent understanding of how they ought to be used. Third, with respect to the Kleypas decision, I am well on it, but this is back to the point that was referenced by Mr. Green on the Kansas Supreme Court's referencing of Kansas case law.","start":3535.885,"stop":3556.33,"duration":20.44},{"text":"I would merely point this Court to what this Court itself said in rejecting precisely the same argument in the Marsh case -- it's at page 169 -- where the Court ultimately concluded Kleypas itself -- State law case -- Kleypas itself rested on Federal law.","start":3556.33,"stop":3571.88,"duration":15.55},{"text":"And the same is true here. The Kansas --","start":3571.88,"stop":3574.35,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Harman didn't.","start":3574.35,"stop":3576.125,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry?","start":3576.125,"stop":3577.52,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Harman didn't.","start":3577.52,"stop":3578.825,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":3578.825,"stop":3580.74,"duration":1.91},{"text":"Harman was not a death penalty case.","start":3580.74,"stop":3581.97,"duration":1.23},{"text":"It was a pre-death penalty case --","start":3581.97,"stop":3583.17,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":3583.17,"stop":3583.29,"duration":0.12},{"text":"But they say just what they said here.","start":3583.29,"stop":3584.72,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"And beyond that, Harman was a 1993 case, barely after this Court --","start":3584.72,"stop":3589.06,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But then as a succession of references back.","start":3589.06,"stop":3591.535,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3591.535,"stop":3591.815,"duration":0.28},{"text":"But the point, Your Honor, is that when the Kansas Supreme Court talked about Harman, this Court only three years previously had laid down the rule that governs this case. It is now well developed what the Eighth Amendment rule is.","start":3591.815,"stop":3604.04,"duration":12.22},{"text":"Harman doesn't say anything about what this Court has been asked to decide. And finally, I would urge the Court to end, I suppose, where we began, which is there's Eighth Amendment error here.","start":3604.04,"stop":3617.295,"duration":13.26},{"text":"And absent correction of that Eighth Amendment error by this Court, it will be the Eighth Amendment interpretation given by the Kansas Supreme Court that disposes of this case, disposes of the other similarly situated cases in Kansas --","start":3617.295,"stop":3629.25,"duration":11.95}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"As we said this -- so as we said, just that.","start":3629.25,"stop":3631.48,"duration":2.23},{"text":"Four sentences you quote, they're wrong. Now, as to whether the -- the instruction in content here was too confusing because of the placement all the arguments you heard, they didn't really go into that.","start":3631.48,"stop":3642.62,"duration":11.14},{"text":"Nor did they really go into the question of State law.","start":3642.62,"stop":3644.95,"duration":2.33},{"text":"Nor did they get into the question of whether the new State law is retroactive. All those remain open on remand for the parties to ask the Court to consider it, and if the Court decides it's appropriate to raise it at that time, to consider it.","start":3644.95,"stop":3659.025,"duration":14.08},{"text":"Is that satisfactory to you?","start":3659.025,"stop":3660.43,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Derek Schmidt","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Justice Breyer. Obviously, we'll deal with whatever State law questions may arise subsequently.","start":3660.43,"stop":3665.17,"duration":4.74},{"text":"But this was --","start":3665.17,"stop":3665.91,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Not just State law, it's the confusion.","start":3665.91,"stop":3667.475,"duration":1.57},{"text":"Sorry.","start":3667.475,"stop":3668.065,"duration":0.59},{"text":"Go ahead.","start":3668.065,"stop":3669.02,"duration":0.95},{"text":"Forget it. I wanted to know if it's satisfactory.","start":3669.02,"stop":3671.19,"duration":2.17},{"text":"The answer is no.","start":3671.19,"stop":3672.945,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel. Case 14-452 is submitted, and we will hear the second question in the other two cases in a moment.","start":3672.945,"stop":0,"duration":-3672.94}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Oct 7, 2015","petitioner":"Kansas","respondent":"Jonathan and Reginald Carr","docket":"14-449","citation":"577US_(2016)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/577/14-449","lowerCourt":"Kansas Supreme Court","grantedOn":"Mar 30, 2015","decidedOn":"Jan 20, 2016"}